WEBVTT

00:10.044 --> 00:21.854
♪

00:21.889 --> 00:23.856
If you are not already
in the know...

00:23.891 --> 00:25.858
We're happy to introduce
for the first time

00:25.893 --> 00:27.393
on our Nashville stage...

00:27.428 --> 00:29.862
Country Music's next
it girl: Adelaide Kay!

00:29.897 --> 00:32.398
So Adelaide, we heard that
you're gonna be a part

00:32.433 --> 00:34.400
of the Christmas Eve
showcase at the Palace,

00:34.435 --> 00:36.101
where you'll be
performing alongside

00:36.137 --> 00:38.804
some of country music's
greatest stars.

00:38.839 --> 00:41.140
Yes, and it's less than
two weeks away.

00:41.175 --> 00:42.474
And how are you feeling?

00:42.510 --> 00:44.543
Humbled, excited...

00:44.979 --> 00:48.047
terrified, but really
this is a dream come true.

00:48.082 --> 00:50.082
<i>And that song you
just sang for us,</i>

00:50.117 --> 00:52.117
your hit single,
"Rock Star."

00:52.153 --> 00:53.218
<i>Who's that about?</i>

00:54.155 --> 00:55.454
We've heard rumors about
you and Cole Wyatt.

00:55.489 --> 00:56.455
Is it true?

00:57.458 --> 01:00.292
Is there someone special
in Adelaide Kay's life?

01:01.128 --> 01:04.096
Uh, is there someone special?

01:04.765 --> 01:05.631
There could be.

01:06.033 --> 01:07.399
Tell us about him!

01:07.601 --> 01:08.700
I really can't.

01:09.770 --> 01:12.504
But I will say that there is
a place in my heart

01:12.540 --> 01:15.240
for something other than
just music, and who knows?

01:15.276 --> 01:17.309
This is the season of miracles.

01:17.344 --> 01:18.677
(LAUGHING)

01:18.712 --> 01:21.413
♪

01:21.449 --> 01:24.650
Ugh, I messed up, I'm always
flat on that last note.

01:24.685 --> 01:25.551
Are you kidding?

01:25.586 --> 01:28.087
You were perfect,
everyone loved you.

01:28.122 --> 01:30.456
Adelaide, you spent
your entire life

01:30.491 --> 01:32.958
dreaming of doing
what you just did.

01:32.993 --> 01:33.892
Try and enjoy it.

01:33.928 --> 01:36.128
What about when they
asked me about Cole,

01:36.163 --> 01:37.763
did I look totally panicked?

01:37.798 --> 01:40.599
Well, you definitely did not
look madly in love

01:40.634 --> 01:42.000
with country music's
hottest star.

01:42.036 --> 01:44.036
Maybe because I am not
madly in love

01:44.071 --> 01:45.871
with country music's
hottest star.

01:45.906 --> 01:46.905
We've discussed this.

01:46.941 --> 01:49.274
You are supposed to
encourage the Cole rumor.

01:49.310 --> 01:50.542
I'm not gonna lie.

01:50.578 --> 01:52.644
Just say there's
someone special.

01:52.680 --> 01:53.779
That's called lying.

01:53.814 --> 01:55.347
<i>No, there's someone special.</i>

01:55.382 --> 01:56.982
You just haven't met him yet.

01:57.017 --> 02:00.252
Besides, pictures don't lie.

02:01.322 --> 02:05.457
They obviously do, because this
was just coffee as friends.

02:05.493 --> 02:07.593
This is your first cover.

02:07.695 --> 02:09.328
How long have you
waited for this?

02:09.363 --> 02:12.865
This whole fake dating thing,
it just doesn't feel like me.

02:12.900 --> 02:14.366
It's the new you.

02:14.401 --> 02:19.071
♪

02:19.106 --> 02:21.340
<i>I forgot to tell you,
I know I said</i>

02:21.375 --> 02:23.842
we could stop in Atlanta
tomorrow to visit your parents,

02:23.878 --> 02:25.344
"but you just booked
'The Talk."

02:25.379 --> 02:26.478
Gotta get to Philly.

02:26.514 --> 02:29.148
But Russell, I haven't seen
my parents in nearly a year.

02:29.183 --> 02:30.382
They'll see you on TV.

02:30.417 --> 02:31.517
But I promised them.

02:31.552 --> 02:34.219
Adelaide, there are sacrifices
to being a star, okay?

02:34.255 --> 02:36.989
Right now what's important
is for you to stay focused.

02:37.024 --> 02:38.724
Rock Star is climbing
the charts.

02:38.759 --> 02:41.560
Your name is on the tip
of everybody's tongue.

02:41.595 --> 02:43.195
You're gonna be
an overnight success.

02:43.230 --> 02:44.596
A lifetime in the making.

02:44.632 --> 02:46.999
And soon it will
all be worth it.

02:47.034 --> 02:48.534
This is everything
you've always wanted,

02:48.569 --> 02:51.336
and you are so close.

02:52.873 --> 02:53.539
You're right.

02:54.108 --> 02:54.873
Good.

02:56.977 --> 03:07.052
♪

03:07.054 --> 03:23.535
♪

03:23.571 --> 03:25.604
<i>RUSSELL: Bingo,
here we are.</i>

03:27.174 --> 03:28.907
<i>SANDRA: This place
is so cute!</i>

03:31.111 --> 03:33.212
<i>Russell, where did
you find this place?</i>

03:33.447 --> 03:34.947
<i>RUSSELL: Hey,
that's what I do.</i>

03:35.516 --> 03:37.649
It's adorable, where are we?

03:37.685 --> 03:38.717
<i>Preston, Virginia.</i>

03:38.752 --> 03:40.652
You have tomorrow off,
so I thought it'd be nice

03:40.688 --> 03:42.955
if we slept in a real bed.

03:46.427 --> 03:47.226
This is cute.

03:47.328 --> 03:48.193
Yeah.

03:48.429 --> 03:55.801
♪

03:55.836 --> 03:57.603
I'll go let them know
we're here.

03:58.439 --> 03:59.438
I'm famished.

03:59.473 --> 04:01.139
Well, don't get too excited.

04:01.175 --> 04:02.241
Russell called ahead.

04:02.276 --> 04:03.542
Russell called ahead.

04:06.113 --> 04:06.979
(SIGH)

04:08.048 --> 04:09.581
I am wistfully remembering
the days when I used to

04:09.617 --> 04:11.316
choose and portion my own food.

04:11.819 --> 04:14.319
Eat up, it's a very healthy,
perfectly balanced meal.

04:15.689 --> 04:17.422
A really healthy,
perfectly balanced meal

04:17.458 --> 04:18.923
is a cookie in each hand.

04:18.959 --> 04:21.493
(LAUGHS)

04:22.329 --> 04:29.801
(HUMMING)

04:29.837 --> 04:33.405
That magic cheer that means
Christmas time...

04:34.041 --> 04:36.675
And now I need a word
that rhymes.

04:37.378 --> 04:38.644
<i>SANDRA: What are
you doing?</i>

04:39.179 --> 04:40.412
Writing a song.

04:40.914 --> 04:41.780
Trying to.

04:42.650 --> 04:44.716
I'm thinking a country
Christmas song.

04:44.752 --> 04:46.218
What do you have so far?

04:46.253 --> 04:48.420
An empty page and determination?

04:48.922 --> 04:50.622
Not a bad start.

04:50.991 --> 04:53.558
Well, whatever you write,
I'm sure it'll be a hit.

04:53.594 --> 04:56.295
You're obviously forgetting
about the spectacular failure

04:56.330 --> 04:58.530
of my self-composed
debut album.

04:58.632 --> 05:00.565
Girl, I've been with you
since you boarded

05:00.601 --> 05:02.234
this country music train.

05:02.269 --> 05:04.336
You're legit.

05:05.739 --> 05:07.039
<i>RUSSELL: Okay,
let's talk schedule.</i>

05:07.074 --> 05:09.074
11 days until
Christmas Eve at the Palace,

05:09.109 --> 05:11.076
we have "The Talk"
radio show on Friday.

05:11.111 --> 05:15.147
Big holiday theme, so here are
some jokes the PR team wrote.

05:15.516 --> 05:16.682
Speaking of writing...

05:16.717 --> 05:21.119
Yeah, speaking of writing,
Bobby sent over the new song.

05:22.022 --> 05:23.221
Here, have a listen.

05:24.124 --> 05:24.890
<i>(MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

05:24.925 --> 05:26.658
<i>♪ And I'm ♪
♪ thinking about, ♪</i>

05:26.694 --> 05:28.694
<i>♪ just thinking ♪
♪ about that kiss ♪</i>

05:28.729 --> 05:30.929
This sounds exactly
like my last song.

05:30.964 --> 05:33.498
Russell, I'm 28 years old.

05:33.534 --> 05:34.499
25 on paper.

05:34.535 --> 05:37.002
Old enough that I have to
stop singing about

05:37.037 --> 05:39.171
the cute boy at the bus stop.

05:39.273 --> 05:40.772
I wanna write my own lyrics.

05:40.808 --> 05:41.973
Adelaide...

05:42.009 --> 05:45.177
One song, and I can maybe
sing it at the Palace concert

05:45.212 --> 05:47.913
and show my fans
who I really am.

05:47.948 --> 05:50.949
You tried writing before,
and it didn't work out.

05:50.984 --> 05:52.150
That was years ago!

05:52.186 --> 05:54.986
<i>Before I started steering you
in the right direction.</i>

05:55.155 --> 05:58.256
Adelaide, we've only been
working together one year,

05:58.292 --> 06:00.726
and already I have you
on the Palace bill,

06:00.761 --> 06:03.261
so just trust me.

06:03.897 --> 06:08.834
You are a great singer,
but writing is hard.

06:08.936 --> 06:11.536
<i>So you just keep
hitting the high notes,</i>

06:11.939 --> 06:13.438
and leave the rest to us.

06:15.109 --> 06:15.841
Alright.

06:21.749 --> 06:24.049
(SIGHS)

06:24.151 --> 06:34.259
(GUITAR PLAYING)

06:34.261 --> 07:03.522
(GUITAR PLAYING)

07:03.557 --> 07:04.890
That's a good tune.

07:05.192 --> 07:05.957
What is it?

07:08.829 --> 07:10.262
Nothing really, just...

07:10.798 --> 07:12.564
Just playing around,
it's just music.

07:12.666 --> 07:13.999
It's never just music.

07:14.468 --> 07:15.500
It's catchy.

07:15.736 --> 07:17.002
Got yourself an ear worm.

07:17.738 --> 07:18.837
An ear worm, what's that?

07:18.872 --> 07:21.506
You know, something that
wiggles it's way into your mind

07:21.542 --> 07:22.574
and won't let go.

07:24.044 --> 07:25.644
Yeah I know what you mean.

07:25.913 --> 07:27.012
<i>(PHONE VIBRATES)</i>

07:33.220 --> 07:34.186
Better go.

07:34.822 --> 07:35.520
Bye.

07:40.928 --> 07:41.359
<i>Bye.</i>

07:41.395 --> 07:53.305
♪

07:53.340 --> 07:54.439
<i>(KNOCKING)</i>

07:57.110 --> 07:59.144
Hey, time to get up.

07:59.947 --> 08:01.313
It's my day off.

08:01.582 --> 08:04.216
Russell said that's why
he let you sleep late.

08:04.751 --> 08:05.550
Let's go.

08:06.553 --> 08:07.919
Seven AM pilates,
eight AM call with Bobby,

08:07.955 --> 08:09.488
and then we hit the road.

08:09.523 --> 08:11.490
Good thing it's my day off.

08:12.526 --> 08:13.658
Chocolate chip?

08:17.030 --> 08:17.963
Don't tell Russell.

08:19.766 --> 08:21.032
You're the best.

08:21.134 --> 08:28.039
♪

08:28.075 --> 08:28.840
Where's Sandra and Russell?

08:28.876 --> 08:30.542
<i>They've gone to get some coffee.</i>

08:30.577 --> 08:32.544
Will you tell them
to hold onto mine?

08:32.578 --> 08:36.047
I'm gonna go in my room and
work and work on the new songs.

08:36.082 --> 08:37.782
I'll make sure no one
bothers you.

08:37.818 --> 08:38.750
Thanks.

08:42.756 --> 08:55.800
♪

08:55.836 --> 08:56.668
Where's Adelaide?

08:57.237 --> 08:58.937
Already on board,
working in her room.

08:58.972 --> 09:00.272
Great, let's hit the road.

09:02.142 --> 09:03.408
♪

09:03.443 --> 09:07.045
<i>DYLAN: Hey, can you just take
this and put it over there,</i>

09:07.080 --> 09:08.813
and then that one on that side?

09:08.849 --> 09:10.215
Don't cross 'em.

09:10.250 --> 09:15.987
♪

09:16.023 --> 09:17.255
<i>Hey, you again.</i>

09:17.357 --> 09:18.156
What's all this?

09:19.526 --> 09:21.293
Clearly you're not
from around here.

09:21.328 --> 09:22.294
How could you tell?

09:22.329 --> 09:24.896
Well, for one, I know
everybody in this town.

09:25.098 --> 09:27.232
And two, the Preston
tree lighting ceremony

09:27.267 --> 09:28.667
is famous around these parts.

09:28.702 --> 09:30.502
Ooh, tree lighting.

09:30.537 --> 09:31.369
Sounds fun.

09:34.041 --> 09:34.639
What?

09:35.776 --> 09:38.944
Sorry, it's just you look
exactly like Adelaide Kay.

09:39.947 --> 09:40.912
You know, the singer?

09:40.948 --> 09:41.913
You know Adelaide Kay?

09:41.949 --> 09:44.649
Yeah, I get told that
I look like her a lot.

09:44.685 --> 09:46.284
Um, are you a fan?

09:47.187 --> 09:48.553
I like her early stuff.

09:48.989 --> 09:51.556
Yeah, her first album was great.

09:52.225 --> 09:54.192
I didn't think anyone
listened to that.

09:54.227 --> 09:54.960
I did.

09:55.762 --> 09:57.329
That ballad is a
real heart ripper.

09:58.865 --> 10:00.665
What about the new stuff?

10:02.135 --> 10:03.568
Not my taste really.

10:03.837 --> 10:04.769
Oh yeah, why?

10:04.805 --> 10:05.937
Why's that?

10:05.973 --> 10:06.905
Well...

10:07.174 --> 10:08.940
Seems a bit manufactured.

10:09.643 --> 10:11.676
None of her songs
really have any heart.

10:11.712 --> 10:14.245
Well maybe she's still
searching for the heart.

10:15.148 --> 10:15.947
Maybe.

10:16.883 --> 10:18.083
Maybe she sold it.

10:18.185 --> 10:19.117
Must be nice.

10:19.853 --> 10:20.619
What's that?

10:21.355 --> 10:22.220
Criticizing from the cheap seats

10:22.255 --> 10:23.955
instead of standing
in the spotlight.

10:23.991 --> 10:25.690
You know, for not
being Adelaide Kay,

10:25.726 --> 10:27.792
you, uh, you're very
protective over her music.

10:27.828 --> 10:28.526
You know what?

10:28.562 --> 10:29.628
You're right.

10:29.830 --> 10:30.829
It's just music.

10:32.099 --> 10:33.031
See you around.

10:33.133 --> 10:40.872
♪

10:40.907 --> 10:41.673
What?

10:41.708 --> 10:42.374
No!

10:42.843 --> 10:44.309
No-no-no-no-no.

10:45.612 --> 10:46.511
(SIGHS)

10:46.713 --> 10:47.412
Really?

10:47.447 --> 10:59.457
♪

11:01.294 --> 11:08.733
<i>(GOOD KING WENCESLAS PLAYING)</i>

11:08.769 --> 11:11.736
Excuse me, do you mind
if I use your phone?

11:11.772 --> 11:14.506
I left mine on the bus
and they left without me.

11:14.541 --> 11:15.407
Oh no.

11:15.442 --> 11:17.342
I have definitely
had days like that.

11:17.377 --> 11:19.110
Do you mind if I take this...

11:19.146 --> 11:20.345
No, not at all.

11:20.380 --> 11:22.247
(BUTTONS CLICKING)

11:22.282 --> 11:23.848
(PHONE DIALING)

11:23.884 --> 11:25.483
<i>VOICEMAIL: It's Sandra,
leave a message.</i>

11:25.919 --> 11:26.718
Sandra, it's me.

11:26.753 --> 11:27.519
I'm in Preston.

11:27.554 --> 11:28.453
You guys left me.

11:28.488 --> 11:30.522
When you get this
will you tell Russell

11:30.557 --> 11:32.757
I need you to come back
and get me.

11:32.793 --> 11:36.261
Um, if you get this in
the next couple minutes,

11:36.296 --> 11:37.962
you can call this number back.

11:37.998 --> 11:39.330
Okay, bye.

11:39.800 --> 11:41.766
<i>HAILEY: Oh and if
they ask for Spruce,</i>

11:41.802 --> 11:44.035
just tell them we have
more coming in tomorrow.

11:44.071 --> 11:45.036
Always happy to help.

11:45.072 --> 11:47.238
No answer, but thank you.

11:47.274 --> 11:49.674
Well, which direction
are you headed in?

11:49.843 --> 11:51.943
Uh, North, Philadelphia.

11:52.412 --> 11:55.213
Well I'm headed home now,
and we live 10 minutes North.

11:55.248 --> 11:56.314
Why don't you come along?

11:56.349 --> 11:59.217
And if your ride calls
they can pick you up there,

11:59.252 --> 12:01.753
and if not, I can drive you
back here later.

12:02.122 --> 12:03.388
Okay, thank you.

12:03.623 --> 12:05.457
Oh, I'm Hailey, by the way.

12:05.492 --> 12:06.091
I'm...

12:07.327 --> 12:07.926
Addie.

12:08.595 --> 12:09.427
Nice to meet you, Addie.

12:09.463 --> 12:10.462
Nice to meet you.

12:11.732 --> 12:13.998
<i>RADIO HOST: Here is a hot new
track called "Rock Star."</i>

12:14.034 --> 12:15.934
<i>I think you're
all gonna like it.</i>

12:15.969 --> 12:20.805
♪

12:20.841 --> 12:23.908
<i>♪ Sittin' in the ♪
♪ bed tonight ♪</i>

12:23.944 --> 12:26.311
Oh, I love this song!

12:26.346 --> 12:28.413
<i>I can never remember
the singer's name.</i>

12:28.448 --> 12:29.914
<i>Sometimes I think
everything I know</i>

12:29.950 --> 12:32.317
is about boys and farming.

12:32.652 --> 12:33.451
Really?

12:33.487 --> 12:34.619
I don't know anything
about that...

12:34.654 --> 12:36.121
Well, farming.

12:36.156 --> 12:37.789
I know enough about boys.

12:37.824 --> 12:38.957
(LAUGHS)

12:38.992 --> 12:40.492
I am a city girl.

12:40.527 --> 12:42.827
I am soothed by the sounds
of honking horns

12:42.863 --> 12:44.629
and the smell of trash.

12:44.664 --> 12:47.265
Well then, I am
definitely a farm girl.

12:47.300 --> 12:49.534
I own more pairs of
galoshes than heels.

12:49.569 --> 12:50.468
What's a galosh?

12:50.904 --> 12:51.669
Good one.

12:52.139 --> 12:52.737
Just kidding.

12:54.708 --> 12:56.441
See that tree line
on the horizon?

12:56.476 --> 12:57.175
Mhm.

12:57.210 --> 12:58.910
That is the back
of the property.

12:59.079 --> 13:00.478
So pretty.

13:00.514 --> 13:10.588
♪

13:10.590 --> 13:21.533
♪

13:21.568 --> 13:23.501
So, this is our house.

13:23.603 --> 13:26.304
We grow the trees here
and then sell them in town.

13:26.540 --> 13:27.405
It's beautiful.

13:27.440 --> 13:29.007
C'mon, I want you
to meet my parents.

13:29.042 --> 13:42.253
♪

13:42.289 --> 13:43.021
<i>HAILEY: Hey!</i>

13:43.056 --> 13:43.688
Thanks.

13:43.723 --> 13:44.389
Hey!

13:44.491 --> 13:45.356
Hi!

13:45.458 --> 13:46.457
Oh, this is Addie,

13:46.493 --> 13:48.693
Addie missed her bus
and got stranded in town.

13:48.728 --> 13:50.195
So I gave her a ride.

13:50.230 --> 13:51.262
These are my parents.

13:51.298 --> 13:52.597
Hi, I'm Emma.

13:52.632 --> 13:53.164
Hi.

13:53.200 --> 13:54.065
Dale.

13:54.167 --> 13:54.632
Hi.

13:54.668 --> 13:55.366
Happy to have ya.

13:55.402 --> 13:57.802
Thank you, your farm
is really...

13:58.638 --> 13:59.737
full of trees.

13:59.773 --> 14:00.939
(LAUGHS)

14:00.974 --> 14:03.007
Spoken like a true city girl.

14:03.109 --> 14:06.211
And I should know, I'm a
reformed city girl myself.

14:06.246 --> 14:06.845
<i>ADDIE: Really?</i>

14:06.880 --> 14:07.846
What brought you out here?

14:07.881 --> 14:11.549
I fell in love with this one,
and after him,

14:11.585 --> 14:13.585
I fell in love with these woods.

14:13.620 --> 14:15.620
So, when it came to pick a job,

14:15.655 --> 14:18.423
we just thought, "How about
a Christmas tree farm?"

14:18.458 --> 14:20.391
She was kind enough to hire me.

14:20.894 --> 14:22.594
You had no choice.

14:25.732 --> 14:26.731
What's he doing here?

14:27.634 --> 14:28.466
<i>HAILEY: That's Dylan,
my brother.</i>

14:28.501 --> 14:35.039
♪

14:35.075 --> 14:36.875
You uh, already know each other?

14:36.910 --> 14:39.878
Yeah, I met Dylan downtown
playing his guitar.

14:39.913 --> 14:41.112
<i>EMMA: Isn't he talented?</i>

14:41.147 --> 14:44.115
I have been president of his
fan club since he was a baby.

14:44.150 --> 14:46.384
Actually when he was little,
he used to say,

14:46.419 --> 14:49.120
"Mom, when I grow up
I want to be a musician."

14:49.155 --> 14:52.223
And I'd say, "Honey, I'm pretty
sure you can't do both."

14:52.259 --> 14:55.460
We were hoping he'd head up to
Nashville and become a big star.

14:55.495 --> 14:57.729
Well lucky for you guys,
I'm not going anywhere.

14:57.764 --> 14:58.696
<i>DALE: Uh-huh.</i>

14:59.833 --> 15:02.467
Hailey, why don't we show Addie
what we do around here?

15:03.336 --> 15:04.135
Addie?

15:04.938 --> 15:06.638
<i>That's a bit of an unusual name.</i>

15:06.673 --> 15:08.907
What is it short for something?

15:11.177 --> 15:14.746
Hey, it's ten days
until Christmas Eve,

15:14.781 --> 15:16.981
this is the last stretch
of our busy season.

15:17.017 --> 15:19.450
Addie, how would you
like to experience

15:19.486 --> 15:22.921
the inexpressible joy of
netting a Christmas tree?

15:23.857 --> 15:28.159
Uh, could I have
a different job?

15:29.462 --> 15:31.829
You could untangle
those Christmas lights.

15:32.065 --> 15:35.166
Untangling those lights would be
the true miracle of Christmas.

15:35.268 --> 15:37.001
We'll need a bigger
miracle than that.

15:37.037 --> 15:37.602
Hailey.

15:37.637 --> 15:37.936
What?

15:37.971 --> 15:38.736
It's true.

15:38.772 --> 15:39.671
<i>We'll talk about
it later, honey.</i>

15:39.706 --> 15:41.873
Dylan, we were in
the middle of netting,

15:41.908 --> 15:45.143
so how about you take
Ms. Addie on a tour of the farm?

15:45.178 --> 15:46.644
Oh, I don't need a tour.

15:46.680 --> 15:47.879
She doesn't need a tour.

15:47.914 --> 15:49.080
Mind your manners.

15:50.817 --> 15:51.516
Sure.

15:51.751 --> 15:58.289
♪

15:58.325 --> 15:59.357
Thank you.

16:00.393 --> 16:01.326
You're netting.

16:01.728 --> 16:02.427
Ugh.

16:02.529 --> 16:15.373
♪

16:15.408 --> 16:18.609
So, is there something
you want to tell me?

16:18.912 --> 16:20.945
Is there something
you want to tell me?

16:22.849 --> 16:28.052
Yeah, that's a Balsam Fir,
over there we have Tamarack,

16:28.088 --> 16:32.056
Spruce and for the
traditionalists, Scotch Pine.

16:34.894 --> 16:38.363
These are all types of trees
that we have on the farm.

16:39.799 --> 16:41.499
Just in case you're confused,

16:41.534 --> 16:44.802
a tree is a woody
perennial plant.

16:45.972 --> 16:49.574
Here I thought a Christmas tree,
was just a Christmas tree.

16:49.609 --> 16:51.075
No, no much more than that.

16:51.111 --> 16:53.578
Although you do strike me
as the kind of person

16:53.613 --> 16:55.913
that buys a fake
plastic tree every year.

16:56.016 --> 16:58.883
Oh actually, I just decorate
a potted plant.

17:02.255 --> 17:05.589
So um, what do you do
on a tree farm?

17:05.625 --> 17:09.527
I'd think that the trees sort
of take care of themselves.

17:09.628 --> 17:10.828
No, not...
Opposite actually.

17:10.864 --> 17:14.298
We don't just plant the seed
and wait for the tree to grow.

17:14.334 --> 17:16.968
A Christmas tree farm is a
constant battle against drought,

17:17.002 --> 17:21.439
insects, heat, frost;
Even a 5 year-old sapling

17:21.473 --> 17:24.041
still takes 10 years before
it reaches maturity.

17:24.077 --> 17:26.778
That's 15 years for every tree
we have on this farm.

17:26.813 --> 17:29.047
It's a good thing
we love what we do.

17:29.082 --> 17:31.115
(SNIFFS)

17:31.151 --> 17:32.350
You smell that?

17:33.753 --> 17:35.920
Smells like a
giant air freshener.

17:37.457 --> 17:38.589
It's fresh snow.

17:39.659 --> 17:41.092
These woods and the snow,

17:41.194 --> 17:43.394
I don't think there's
any place I'd rather be.

17:43.430 --> 17:45.263
Not on stage playing music?

17:45.932 --> 17:46.731
You're good.

17:46.933 --> 17:47.698
Oh yeah?

17:47.801 --> 17:51.069
I just know that
real talent is rare.

17:51.171 --> 17:52.603
You should be in
Nashville playing,

17:52.639 --> 17:53.905
so you can be heard.

17:55.975 --> 17:57.542
My place is in Preston.

17:57.977 --> 17:59.410
With my family.

18:07.654 --> 18:09.020
<i>♪ S</i>
doing?

18:09.055 --> 18:10.588
Salting the driveway.

18:10.623 --> 18:12.890
It prevents the ice
from forming.

18:13.460 --> 18:14.492
What?

18:14.527 --> 18:16.327
I'm from Atlanta, if it
snows more than an inch

18:16.362 --> 18:18.696
the city shuts down
for snowpocalpyse.

18:18.731 --> 18:19.697
(LAUGHING)

18:19.732 --> 18:21.165
(PHONE RINGING)

18:21.568 --> 18:23.134
Oh, I think it's for you.

18:25.872 --> 18:26.604
Hello?

18:26.706 --> 18:27.839
Adelaide, you okay?

18:28.074 --> 18:28.773
Yeah, I'm fine.

18:28.808 --> 18:30.775
Well, good news and bad news.

18:30.810 --> 18:32.777
There's been an accident,
the highway is closed.

18:32.812 --> 18:34.512
<i>And there's a
snowstorm on the way,</i>

18:34.547 --> 18:35.780
go back to the bnb.

18:35.815 --> 18:38.015
We'll pick you up
as soon as we can.

18:38.051 --> 18:39.350
And the good news?

18:39.385 --> 18:41.986
You and Cole have
made another cover.

18:42.021 --> 18:42.854
<i>Great.</i>

18:43.189 --> 18:51.629
♪

18:51.664 --> 18:52.997
That was my ride.

18:53.433 --> 18:54.966
I need to get back soon.

18:55.668 --> 18:58.636
So I'm just gonna call a cab,
and head back to town.

18:58.671 --> 18:59.670
Absolutely not.

18:59.706 --> 19:02.874
No you'll stay here, yeah,
you'll be our guest.

19:02.976 --> 19:04.642
I couldn't, I don't
even have clothes,

19:04.677 --> 19:05.710
or a toothbrush.

19:05.745 --> 19:07.178
Well, we have that.

19:07.714 --> 19:10.047
You don't even know me,
I'm a stranger.

19:10.083 --> 19:11.249
Emma, hide the silver.

19:11.284 --> 19:12.817
I would if we had some.

19:13.419 --> 19:15.586
<i>You'll stay, and
that's the end of it.</i>

19:15.622 --> 19:17.889
Well, alright.

19:18.191 --> 19:19.223
Thank you.

19:21.094 --> 19:22.326
<i>DALE: I'm out
of salt.</i>

19:22.362 --> 19:24.061
<i>HAILEY: Oh! Uh, I'll pop
into town.</i>

19:24.097 --> 19:26.063
Addie, do you want
to come with me?

19:26.099 --> 19:27.565
I can show you around Preston.

19:27.600 --> 19:28.533
I'd love to.

19:28.568 --> 19:39.243
♪

19:39.279 --> 19:42.013
Obviously Preston goes
crazy for Christmas.

19:42.048 --> 19:43.481
It's impressive.

19:43.583 --> 19:46.083
Everybody does something
for the holiday.

19:46.119 --> 19:49.187
When I was a kid, I waited
all year for Christmas.

19:49.222 --> 19:50.688
Ugh, me too.

19:50.790 --> 19:52.823
My family went all out.

19:53.493 --> 19:55.760
I really miss being home
for the holidays.

19:58.064 --> 20:01.265
Every tree that you see here
in town, including this one,

20:01.301 --> 20:02.466
came from our farm.

20:02.502 --> 20:05.603
We've been donating the tree
to the square for 30 years.

20:05.638 --> 20:08.706
And we will be donating it
for 30 more.

20:12.612 --> 20:13.578
Hey, Bev.

20:13.613 --> 20:15.246
Oh, Hailey!

20:17.150 --> 20:19.150
Oh, Bev this is
my new friend Addie.

20:19.185 --> 20:20.818
Nice to meet you, sweetheart.

20:20.853 --> 20:22.386
(LAUGHS)

20:22.422 --> 20:23.721
Nice to meet you too.

20:23.756 --> 20:24.956
Have we met before?

20:24.991 --> 20:26.924
You look so familiar.

20:27.627 --> 20:28.926
I get that a lot.

20:29.762 --> 20:32.463
Hailey, I heard about the farm.

20:32.932 --> 20:34.532
How's your family doing?

20:34.634 --> 20:35.099
We're okay.

20:35.134 --> 20:36.767
We're not giving up.

20:37.003 --> 20:39.103
Listen, I know how
proud your folks are,

20:39.138 --> 20:40.605
too proud for their own good.

20:40.640 --> 20:43.608
So let's not tell them,
but the salt bags are on me.

20:43.643 --> 20:44.342
<i>Oh no, no...</i>

20:44.377 --> 20:45.042
No, no.

20:45.078 --> 20:46.410
It's an early Christmas gift.

20:46.446 --> 20:47.912
And if there's
anything you need,

20:47.947 --> 20:49.647
anything at all.

20:49.682 --> 20:50.781
Come to me.

20:50.817 --> 20:51.816
Thank you.

20:52.619 --> 20:54.051
Merry Christmas.

20:54.621 --> 20:55.753
Nice to meet you.

20:59.959 --> 21:02.994
Hailey, what was Bev
saying about the farm?

21:03.029 --> 21:05.830
Um, we're behind
on the mortgage.

21:05.865 --> 21:08.132
And the bank is
threatening to foreclose.

21:08.234 --> 21:09.800
I'm so sorry.

21:09.836 --> 21:13.104
Yeah, the big automotive
plant outside town closed down,

21:13.139 --> 21:15.339
and it hit Preston pretty hard.

21:15.808 --> 21:17.608
Coupled with last
year's drought,

21:17.644 --> 21:20.177
we lost a few trees,
missed a few payments,

21:20.213 --> 21:22.813
and just haven't
been able to recover.

21:22.849 --> 21:24.348
But you will recover, right?

21:24.684 --> 21:25.383
I hope so.

21:27.353 --> 21:29.253
That's why Dylan won't leave.

21:29.555 --> 21:32.223
We've tried to get him
to go, but he won't.

21:32.258 --> 21:33.691
He stays for us.

21:33.926 --> 21:35.293
Pretty selfless of him.

21:36.663 --> 21:38.562
Selfless is saying
you don't like pie

21:38.598 --> 21:40.598
when there isn't
enough to go around.

21:41.534 --> 21:43.034
It's something my
mom always says.

21:43.836 --> 21:46.170
Well, I call that heroic.

21:46.406 --> 21:53.744
♪

21:53.780 --> 21:56.647
<i>(CHATTER)</i>

21:56.683 --> 21:57.181
Thank you.

21:57.216 --> 21:58.149
This looks so good.

21:58.184 --> 21:58.716
Alright.

21:58.751 --> 21:59.917
Can I have the corn?

21:59.952 --> 22:00.985
Hurry up.

22:01.087 --> 22:03.154
This all looks delicious.

22:03.189 --> 22:04.088
Thank you.

22:04.123 --> 22:05.723
<i>HAILEY: Mom, this
looks so amazing.</i>

22:05.758 --> 22:06.824
Like a treat.

22:07.260 --> 22:08.793
You can take more Addie.

22:09.095 --> 22:11.662
Especially these potatoes,
they're from our garden.

22:11.698 --> 22:13.164
So eat up, don't be shy.

22:13.199 --> 22:15.666
This is the best meal
I've had in a while.

22:15.702 --> 22:17.368
And I do love my food.

22:17.403 --> 22:20.438
Well, people who love food
are my favourite people.

22:20.473 --> 22:21.939
Well then you're gonna like me.

22:21.974 --> 22:23.441
What do you like to cook?

22:23.476 --> 22:25.443
Um, I'm not actually
much of a cook.

22:25.478 --> 22:27.712
Oh c'mon I bet that
you're a great cook.

22:27.747 --> 22:28.713
What's your signature dish?

22:28.748 --> 22:30.748
Um, something burnt?

22:30.783 --> 22:32.883
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

22:32.919 --> 22:34.285
Okay, you're not a cook.

22:34.320 --> 22:35.786
Tell us more
about yourself, Addie.

22:35.822 --> 22:38.289
Yeah, where you coming in
from, where you headed to?

22:38.324 --> 22:40.257
What are you doing
for the holidays?

22:40.293 --> 22:43.027
Yeah Addie,
any plans for Christmas?

22:44.831 --> 22:49.533
I am actually
working this Christmas.

22:49.569 --> 22:50.768
Doing what?

22:50.870 --> 22:52.670
I'm, um...

22:53.973 --> 22:54.939
I know something about Addie

22:54.974 --> 22:57.375
that I think everyone
will find interesting.

22:57.410 --> 22:58.275
<i>EMMA: Do tell.</i>

22:58.778 --> 22:59.910
Addie...

23:02.014 --> 23:03.447
doesn't have a Christmas tree.

23:03.649 --> 23:04.915
(GASPING)

23:04.951 --> 23:05.516
<i>HAILEY: What?</i>

23:05.551 --> 23:07.284
<i>EMMA: Are you serious?!</i>

23:07.387 --> 23:08.619
(SCOFFING)

23:08.654 --> 23:10.054
Oh jeez, the pies.

23:10.590 --> 23:12.723
You don't have a Christmas tree?

23:12.759 --> 23:14.658
Well I-I have a
Christmas tree,

23:14.694 --> 23:17.128
I-I just haven't put
it together yet.

23:17.163 --> 23:18.629
Oh that is a holiday sacrilege.

23:18.664 --> 23:21.432
You're gonna have to
take one of ours home with ya'.

23:21.467 --> 23:22.466
I would love to.

23:22.502 --> 23:23.501
<i>EMMA: Okay.</i>

23:23.536 --> 23:24.702
There we go!

23:25.438 --> 23:27.238
Oh, Dale, really?

23:27.273 --> 23:28.506
Yes, really.

23:28.541 --> 23:31.308
I think dessert is one of the
most important meals of the day.

23:31.344 --> 23:34.311
Well, I would live on a
farm if we could raise pie.

23:34.347 --> 23:35.513
Here's our new daughter.

23:35.548 --> 23:37.481
(LAUGHING)

23:37.517 --> 23:47.591
♪

23:47.593 --> 24:08.379
♪

24:08.414 --> 24:11.148
I brought you pajamas
and a toothbrush, and stuff.

24:11.184 --> 24:11.749
Thank you.

24:12.318 --> 24:13.918
Um, what is all this?

24:14.387 --> 24:16.153
Oh, I make wreaths.

24:16.656 --> 24:17.988
They're gorgeous.

24:18.391 --> 24:20.291
Well they're easy,
do you wanna learn?

24:20.893 --> 24:21.659
Yeah.

24:22.995 --> 24:23.527
Okay.

24:23.563 --> 24:23.961
So.

24:23.996 --> 24:25.629
Take your base.

24:25.665 --> 24:26.897
There you go.

24:26.933 --> 24:30.100
I've got mine started and then
you cut a couple branches here...

24:30.269 --> 24:33.204
There you go, and you're just
gonna want to straighten out

24:33.239 --> 24:37.174
the branches to make sure
they look nice and neat.

24:37.677 --> 24:40.144
And then you're just
gonna lay it on the base,

24:40.179 --> 24:44.782
and then you're gonna take your
wire and attach it to the base.

24:45.685 --> 24:47.718
And you do that
all the way around,

24:48.054 --> 24:49.553
you'll get the hang of it.

24:49.856 --> 24:52.356
And then you get to add
ribbons and pinecones,

24:52.391 --> 24:54.124
and decorate it
however you want.

24:54.594 --> 24:56.026
So do you sell these?

24:57.263 --> 25:00.564
I've thought about it but I
don't think they're good enough.

25:00.867 --> 25:04.568
I do have lots of other ideas
on ways to save the farm though.

25:04.904 --> 25:05.636
Yeah?
Like what?

25:06.405 --> 25:08.572
Well, I want to
expand the business.

25:08.608 --> 25:11.342
I want families to be able
to come to the farm

25:11.377 --> 25:12.877
to buy their trees.

25:12.912 --> 25:16.947
And we could have sleigh
rides and a snack bar.

25:16.983 --> 25:19.450
There could be an
ice skating rink and concerts.

25:19.485 --> 25:22.052
It would be like
a little Winter Wonderland.

25:22.388 --> 25:23.888
It sounds perfect.

25:24.457 --> 25:26.690
Have you talked to
your parents about it?

25:26.726 --> 25:30.761
I've tried, but we never
have the money.

25:31.898 --> 25:36.433
Anyway, it's a dream,
but it's just a dream.

25:37.103 --> 25:39.703
Kind of like me
making this wreath?

25:41.307 --> 25:42.540
(LAUGHING)

25:44.210 --> 25:46.844
♪

25:46.879 --> 25:49.146
(HUMMING)

25:49.181 --> 25:53.050
<i>♪ Hearin' all the ♪
♪ Christmas songs ♪</i>

25:53.085 --> 25:57.421
<i>♪ Waitin' for ♪
♪ old Santa Claus ♪</i>

25:57.590 --> 26:00.124
<i>♪ Kiss under ♪
♪ the mistletoe ♪</i>

26:00.560 --> 26:01.825
(HUMMING)

26:01.861 --> 26:03.661
<i>(INDISTINCT CHATTER)</i>

26:03.696 --> 26:05.396
<i>HAILEY: I feel like
you're not listening.</i>

26:05.431 --> 26:06.196
<i>You don't get it.</i>

26:06.232 --> 26:07.698
<i>We... we have to
do something!</i>

26:07.733 --> 26:09.199
<i>EMMA: What
exactly is it you...</i>

26:09.235 --> 26:11.068
<i>HAILEY: We have
to at least try.</i>

26:11.103 --> 26:11.936
<i>EMMA:
With what money?</i>

26:11.971 --> 26:14.038
Hailey, we can't
even pay the mortgage.

26:14.073 --> 26:15.105
So, what?

26:15.141 --> 26:17.474
We're just supposed to
sit around and do nothing?

26:17.510 --> 26:20.244
Just wait for the
bank to foreclose?

26:20.279 --> 26:22.146
<i>(FOOTSTEPS ON STAIRS)</i>

26:22.181 --> 26:33.857
♪

26:33.893 --> 26:35.292
Christmas decorations!

26:35.394 --> 26:36.093
(GIGGLING)

26:36.128 --> 26:37.227
<i>You wanna help?</i>

26:37.263 --> 26:39.196
Are you gonna make me
untangle more Christmas lights?

26:39.231 --> 26:42.366
Well, if you start now, you
might be done by New Years.

26:42.401 --> 26:43.200
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

26:47.206 --> 26:50.207
Aw, that was
Dylan's first guitar.

26:51.811 --> 26:54.244
<i>So what about you Miss Addie?</i>

26:54.614 --> 26:56.046
What makes you tick?

26:56.616 --> 26:57.982
I also love music.

26:58.884 --> 27:02.219
I work a lot,
which is good, I guess.

27:02.254 --> 27:03.554
Never really home.

27:04.557 --> 27:07.057
I don't get to see
my friends or family much.

27:07.927 --> 27:10.361
I don't really get
moments like this,

27:10.396 --> 27:13.263
so, it's nice being here.

27:13.799 --> 27:15.699
Well, we're happy to have you.

27:18.004 --> 27:21.038
Emma, Hailey told me about
the possible foreclosure.

27:22.241 --> 27:28.545
Oh, uh, well, farmers are
really good at growing things

27:28.581 --> 27:31.548
but not always
as good at selling them.

27:32.118 --> 27:34.018
I would really like to help.

27:34.854 --> 27:35.886
Oh, no.

27:35.921 --> 27:40.224
That is so kind, honey,
really, but we'll be okay.

27:41.694 --> 27:42.926
Yeah, we'll be okay.

27:44.096 --> 27:47.064
Addie, have you seen our stars?

27:47.099 --> 27:51.068
We have the most
brilliant night sky.

27:51.837 --> 27:53.370
You want me to go outside?

27:53.806 --> 27:54.772
In the cold?

27:54.807 --> 27:55.606
Yup.

27:55.708 --> 27:56.507
At night?

27:56.542 --> 27:57.608
(LAUGHING)

27:57.643 --> 27:59.176
Who knows what you'll find.

27:59.211 --> 28:03.914
♪

28:03.949 --> 28:08.619
<i>(FOOTSTEPS ON SNOW)</i>

28:08.654 --> 28:19.997
(PLAYING GUITAR)

28:26.505 --> 28:29.640
Your mom told me
to come see the stars.

28:30.142 --> 28:32.776
Yeah, I bet she did.

28:33.979 --> 28:35.179
The storm is rolling in,

28:35.214 --> 28:37.247
but it's a pretty clear
sky right now.

28:38.017 --> 28:41.085
So this is what's beyond
the blanket of city smog.

28:41.554 --> 28:42.252
Mm-hm.

28:44.523 --> 28:48.192
I bet a country boy like you
knows all the constellations.

28:49.161 --> 28:50.427
Yeah, of course.

28:53.365 --> 28:54.665
What's that?

28:57.503 --> 28:59.536
That is Orion's Belt.

29:01.173 --> 29:02.439
And that?

29:03.676 --> 29:07.277
That is Orion's suspenders.

29:08.247 --> 29:09.847
(LAUGHING)

29:11.183 --> 29:14.184
That is Ursa Major.

29:14.286 --> 29:16.887
That is Cassiopeia.

29:18.791 --> 29:20.157
Wow, you know your stars.

29:20.593 --> 29:22.326
I've wished on
'em so many times,

29:22.361 --> 29:23.994
I know them all by name.

29:25.231 --> 29:27.498
Or it takes a star
to know a star,

29:28.467 --> 29:29.233
Adelaide.

29:32.571 --> 29:34.905
I would recognize
your voice anywhere.

29:36.041 --> 29:37.341
And it does have heart.

29:38.144 --> 29:38.976
Maybe.

29:41.213 --> 29:42.546
I'm sorry I lied.

29:44.717 --> 29:47.584
I don't always know
how to be Adelaide Kay.

29:49.588 --> 29:51.922
It's easier to be just Addie.

29:55.594 --> 29:57.528
I should tell your
family the truth.

29:57.563 --> 29:58.195
No.

29:58.898 --> 30:00.497
Your secret is safe with me.

30:04.937 --> 30:06.436
And so is your secret.

30:07.339 --> 30:07.905
Mine?

30:07.940 --> 30:09.072
I don't have a secret.

30:09.942 --> 30:10.707
You don't really
have any interest

30:10.743 --> 30:13.143
in playing music or performing,

30:13.179 --> 30:17.381
or doing the thing
you obviously love?

30:20.119 --> 30:21.385
(CHUCKLING)

30:22.521 --> 30:26.423
Yeah, I'm not one for
standing up in front of people.

30:27.593 --> 30:33.096
And besides, I've got the stars,
lodging close to where I work.

30:33.132 --> 30:34.398
What more do I need?

30:39.271 --> 30:39.837
(SIGHING)

30:39.872 --> 30:43.073
Well, we should turn in.

30:43.175 --> 30:45.075
We have early
mornings around here.

30:47.012 --> 30:48.946
Not as early as my mornings.

30:49.315 --> 30:50.180
Yeah, well, we'll see.

30:50.216 --> 30:52.015
Oh and don't think
being Adelaide Kay

30:52.051 --> 30:54.017
is gonna get you out
of morning chores.

30:54.053 --> 30:55.152
Oh, I don't.

30:55.654 --> 30:57.788
And I'm not
Adelaide Kay, remember?

30:58.524 --> 30:59.857
Just Addie.

30:59.892 --> 31:09.967
♪

31:09.969 --> 31:18.809
♪

31:19.144 --> 31:22.179
♪

31:22.214 --> 31:24.681
<i>RUSSELL: Now, instead we're
missing important promos.</i>

31:24.717 --> 31:25.716
Never mind.

31:25.751 --> 31:26.683
We're snowed in.

31:26.719 --> 31:28.986
We're gonna come for
you as soon as we can.

31:29.021 --> 31:30.354
What about The Talk today?

31:30.689 --> 31:31.955
<i>RUSSELL:
Cole will do it.</i>

31:32.524 --> 31:34.291
You replaced me with Cole Wyatt?

31:34.326 --> 31:35.325
<i>RUSSELL:
Not replacing.</i>

31:35.361 --> 31:37.628
The two of you are
gonna do the show together.

31:37.663 --> 31:39.363
Russell, you can't keep
making these decisions

31:39.398 --> 31:40.898
without consulting me.

31:40.933 --> 31:42.699
<i>RUSSELL: We'll talk
about this later, alright?</i>

31:42.735 --> 31:44.668
Look, talk to Sandra, okay?

31:46.605 --> 31:47.671
(SIGHING)

31:47.706 --> 31:48.605
I know.

31:49.041 --> 31:50.807
So, how's the farm?

31:51.410 --> 31:52.876
Too much fresh air.

31:53.579 --> 31:55.846
No, it's nice.

31:56.582 --> 32:00.684
Emma and Dale are so gracious,
and Hailey is way cooler

32:00.719 --> 32:04.321
than I ever was at 16,
and Dylan...

32:04.623 --> 32:05.489
<i>SANDRA: Dylan?</i>

32:05.524 --> 32:07.157
Wait, there's a Dylan?

32:07.192 --> 32:07.991
Is he cute?

32:08.027 --> 32:09.026
What's he like?

32:09.228 --> 32:13.997
He's like,
I don't know... real.

32:15.034 --> 32:15.933
<i>HAILEY:
Addie, breakfast!</i>

32:15.968 --> 32:17.501
<i>I also brought
you some new clothes.</i>

32:17.536 --> 32:18.535
<i>I hope they fit.</i>

32:18.570 --> 32:19.870
Is she calling you "Addie"?

32:19.905 --> 32:21.571
And what do you mean 'real'?

32:21.607 --> 32:23.840
<i>ADDIE: Sandra, just call
me when the highway opens.</i>

32:23.876 --> 32:24.374
(PHONE BEEP)

32:24.410 --> 32:26.076
(DOOR SLIDING OPEN)

32:26.445 --> 32:27.511
Galoshes!

32:27.813 --> 32:28.979
Amazing.

32:29.748 --> 32:33.884
(PAN SIZZLING)

32:34.386 --> 32:35.185
Morning, Addie.

32:35.220 --> 32:35.953
Morning.

32:35.988 --> 32:36.820
Hi, honey!

32:36.855 --> 32:38.388
Oh, it's ten days
before Christmas.

32:38.424 --> 32:39.923
Why don't you do the honours?

32:40.392 --> 32:43.126
<i>Addie, why don't come over
and help me flip some pancakes?</i>

32:43.162 --> 32:44.394
I'd love to.

32:44.430 --> 32:45.696
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

32:45.731 --> 32:46.663
Oh, wow.

32:47.633 --> 32:50.067
These are Dad's
famous Christmas pancakes.

32:50.169 --> 32:52.803
You guys have, uh, holiday
shaped breakfasts a lot?

32:52.838 --> 32:54.304
<i>DALE: You must
think we're crazy.</i>

32:54.340 --> 32:56.306
As long as the
pancakes are this good,

32:56.342 --> 32:57.407
I'm not judging.

32:57.443 --> 33:00.110
We are not crazy, we're
just a little bit different.

33:00.145 --> 33:04.047
Actually, Addie, there is
a story about a forest that was

33:04.083 --> 33:06.650
full of perfectly straight
trees, but in the centre,

33:06.685 --> 33:09.152
there's a-a crooked tree,
and all of the very,

33:09.188 --> 33:11.888
very straight trees they
laugh at the crooked tree,

33:11.924 --> 33:16.059
until the loggers come and say,
"Take all of the straight ones,

33:16.095 --> 33:19.096
and leave the rest."

33:19.131 --> 33:23.934
(LAUGHING)

33:23.969 --> 33:25.102
We're the rest.

33:25.137 --> 33:32.142
♪

33:33.445 --> 33:35.412
Oh, I, um, I heard on the radio

33:35.447 --> 33:37.948
about this talent
search for musicians,

33:37.983 --> 33:41.218
some sort of a reality
T.V. show or something...

33:44.857 --> 33:46.323
So I loaded the truck up.

33:46.358 --> 33:48.091
I'm gonna head into
town after breakfast.

33:48.127 --> 33:49.593
Oh, I'll come with uhh, Addie,

33:49.628 --> 33:52.095
do you want to stay here
or come with us?

33:52.131 --> 33:54.598
I don't know how
my ride will take so, yeah,

33:54.633 --> 33:55.665
I'll come to town.

33:55.701 --> 33:56.500
Great!

33:56.602 --> 34:00.404
♪

34:01.940 --> 34:06.076
♪

34:06.111 --> 34:08.411
Alright, let's go to work.

34:08.647 --> 34:09.179
What?

34:09.848 --> 34:11.214
Help me unload the truck.

34:11.917 --> 34:13.315
Unload the truck?

34:13.719 --> 34:14.418
Yeah.

34:15.154 --> 34:16.520
Are you serious?

34:19.091 --> 34:22.225
I did spend most of childhood
indoors - singing lessons,

34:22.261 --> 34:26.830
pageants, and heavy lifting
wasn't exactly a pageant talent.

34:26.931 --> 34:29.733
Well, it's time to learn
a new pageant talent.

34:29.768 --> 34:30.600
C'mon.

34:31.469 --> 34:34.471
You grab it by
the base string there,

34:34.505 --> 34:36.239
I'll get it here, you ready?

34:36.341 --> 34:37.040
Yeah.

34:37.141 --> 34:39.743
One, two, three, up.

34:40.646 --> 34:42.846
And down.

34:46.918 --> 34:47.250
Great.

34:47.286 --> 34:48.085
Good job.

34:48.853 --> 34:51.521
Um, just grab it by the head.

34:53.192 --> 34:54.091
Like this?

34:54.193 --> 34:55.257
Yeah, you got it?

34:56.795 --> 34:57.627
Yeah.

34:58.664 --> 34:59.463
Good.

35:01.633 --> 35:04.835
Look at you Addie, you're
going to be a pro in no time.

35:04.870 --> 35:05.635
Oh yeah.

35:05.938 --> 35:07.104
(LAUGHS)

35:07.139 --> 35:09.072
I was actually thinking if
you put your wreaths out here,

35:09.108 --> 35:10.807
maybe you can try and sell them.

35:10.843 --> 35:12.576
I think they'd fly out of here.

35:12.611 --> 35:15.612
I actually think your whole idea
for the farm could really work.

35:18.317 --> 35:19.649
I told Addie.

35:20.886 --> 35:24.121
And I know your parents said
no because it would cost money,

35:24.156 --> 35:26.490
but what if it didn't have to?

35:26.592 --> 35:27.524
What do you mean?

35:27.559 --> 35:29.593
Maybe you have people
who'd want to help.

35:29.628 --> 35:31.128
Like friends or neighbors.

35:31.330 --> 35:33.930
Well, Owen has
the horse and sleigh.

35:33.966 --> 35:37.667
Yeah, and Bev has all of those
decorations just lying around.

35:37.870 --> 35:40.537
What if we built something
to show mom and dad?

35:40.572 --> 35:41.771
Yeah, yeah.

35:41.807 --> 35:43.340
Let's see what happens.

35:43.442 --> 35:46.476
Maybe you could make the
money you need to save the farm.

35:46.512 --> 35:47.844
It's a great idea.

35:47.880 --> 35:53.884
♪

35:53.919 --> 35:56.386
We can go talk to Bev
in the hardware store,

35:56.421 --> 35:57.888
then we can go find Owen.

35:57.923 --> 35:59.389
Oh but-but there's
Owen right there.

35:59.424 --> 35:59.990
Oh, yeah, yeah.

36:00.025 --> 36:01.458
Go get him kid, c'mon.

36:01.493 --> 36:02.692
What if he says no?

36:02.728 --> 36:04.194
And what if he says yes?

36:04.229 --> 36:05.228
C'mon, I'll go with you.

36:05.264 --> 36:07.764
Just speak from the heart,
and it'll be great.

36:09.501 --> 36:10.534
Owen, hi.

36:10.569 --> 36:11.201
I'm Addie.

36:11.236 --> 36:12.536
A friend of the Lapp family.

36:12.571 --> 36:14.037
So nice to meet you Addie.

36:14.072 --> 36:15.338
Dylan, Hailey.

36:15.374 --> 36:18.141
Owen, I was hoping
that you would help us.

36:18.510 --> 36:20.777
I have this idea
for the family farm.

36:21.013 --> 36:22.979
Sure, what would that be?

36:23.015 --> 36:25.348
♪

36:25.384 --> 36:27.217
So, what do you think Bev?

36:27.252 --> 36:28.852
I love your idea, Hailey!

36:28.887 --> 36:30.387
The decorations are all yours.

36:30.422 --> 36:31.188
Thank you.

36:31.223 --> 36:32.722
Come on this way, I'll show you.

36:32.758 --> 36:38.595
♪

36:38.630 --> 36:40.997
Hey, look at these.

36:41.867 --> 36:43.066
You should put them on.

36:43.101 --> 36:43.366
Yeah.

36:43.402 --> 36:43.600
C'mon!

36:43.635 --> 36:44.401
No.

36:44.436 --> 36:45.235
Be a reindeer.

36:45.270 --> 36:46.436
I'm not a reindeer.

36:46.471 --> 36:48.905
<i>RADIO HOST: Alright, off
the top we have special guest,</i>

36:48.941 --> 36:49.773
<i>Cole Wyatt.</i>

36:49.808 --> 36:51.741
<i>So Cole, let's get right to it,</i>

36:51.777 --> 36:54.044
<i>what can you tell us
about you and Adelaide?</i>

36:54.079 --> 36:56.846
<i>COLE: Uh, let's just say there's
something going on between us</i>

36:56.882 --> 36:59.883
<i>that neither of us
really understands.</i>

37:00.552 --> 37:02.752
(CHUCKLES)

37:02.788 --> 37:04.721
Sounds like your boyfriend
really misses you.

37:04.756 --> 37:11.761
♪

37:11.797 --> 37:14.898
Hey, Cole is not my boyfriend.

37:14.933 --> 37:17.400
It's just a publicity stunt
that my manager set up.

37:17.436 --> 37:19.135
It's just the way
things are done.

37:19.171 --> 37:21.137
You pretend to date
people you barely know.

37:21.173 --> 37:23.873
And you sing songs
you know are bad.

37:23.909 --> 37:25.609
Well, do it a different way.

37:25.644 --> 37:28.378
Do it your way, go back
to writing your own songs.

37:28.413 --> 37:29.279
And what?

37:29.314 --> 37:30.413
That album flopped.

37:30.449 --> 37:32.816
I think you were the
only person who listened to it.

37:32.851 --> 37:34.584
But then I started
working with Russell,

37:34.620 --> 37:35.819
and doing it his way.

37:35.854 --> 37:39.756
And now, I have a hit single.

37:39.791 --> 37:41.291
I'm so close.

37:43.662 --> 37:46.396
Except, you know,
suddenly I'm...

37:46.431 --> 37:48.131
Cole Wyatt's girlfriend.

37:48.967 --> 37:52.168
It's just, what if this is
the only way you can do it?

37:52.204 --> 37:53.303
What if it's not?

37:57.342 --> 37:59.142
I'm trying to write
a Christmas song,

37:59.177 --> 38:02.412
to maybe perform at
the Palace concert.

38:02.614 --> 38:04.948
All right, well what
do you have so far?

38:05.217 --> 38:07.250
Frustration
and self-doubt.

38:07.552 --> 38:09.619
Building blocks of
every creative endeavor.

38:09.821 --> 38:11.821
It's just a carol is a big deal.

38:11.857 --> 38:14.090
It's a song that's
supposed to make you feel

38:14.126 --> 38:15.458
the joy of Christmas.

38:15.494 --> 38:17.961
That's a lot of pressure
you put on one song.

38:17.996 --> 38:21.164
Why not instead just think
of what a carol means to you.

38:21.199 --> 38:22.932
What does a carol mean to you?

38:22.968 --> 38:26.002
To me, a carol is
the visiting uncle of songs,

38:26.038 --> 38:28.638
it shows up too early,
way too loud,

38:28.674 --> 38:30.674
and never leaves
when I want it to.

38:32.177 --> 38:32.776
Hey.

38:35.580 --> 38:37.981
A carol makes me feel...

38:39.818 --> 38:43.086
the way I felt as a kid
on Christmas morning.

38:44.222 --> 38:48.191
See, you're good at this,
you should be making music.

38:48.226 --> 38:52.562
♪

38:52.597 --> 38:54.064
Everything is set
for the presentation

38:54.099 --> 38:55.098
for mom and dad tomorrow.

38:55.133 --> 38:57.567
The print shop is
making the flyers for free.

38:57.602 --> 39:00.070
So, I'll hand them out
and get the word out.

39:00.105 --> 39:02.839
Ooh and you should also announce
it at the tree lighting.

39:02.874 --> 39:05.141
If I do, could you
stay for the festival?

39:05.177 --> 39:08.478
<i>You would love it,
there's food and music.</i>

39:10.015 --> 39:10.947
Music?

39:11.616 --> 39:14.217
Maybe you should perform
with the tree lighting.

39:14.252 --> 39:16.152
It'll be great
press for the farm.

39:16.188 --> 39:18.021
(UNEASY CHUCKLE)

39:18.590 --> 39:20.156
<i>(PHONE VIBRATES)</i>

39:20.192 --> 39:21.791
Oh, I think it's for you.

39:22.094 --> 39:25.562
(TEXT TONES)

39:25.664 --> 39:28.865
(TYPING)

39:28.900 --> 39:29.866
Um...

39:29.968 --> 39:30.800
(TEXT TONE)

39:30.836 --> 39:33.002
Would it be all right
with you guys

39:33.038 --> 39:35.004
if I stayed with you
a little longer?

39:35.040 --> 39:36.706
Uh, yeah yeah.

39:36.742 --> 39:38.541
I think that'd be great.

39:38.643 --> 39:42.979
What if I stay longer if you
perform at the tree lighting?

39:43.749 --> 39:44.381
Deal?

39:44.649 --> 39:52.455
♪

39:52.491 --> 39:54.958
Hailey, it's 4 AM,
it's the middle of the night.

39:54.993 --> 39:56.459
Also known as
the farmer's morning.

39:56.495 --> 39:58.728
That's for dairy farmers
that have to milk cows,

39:58.764 --> 40:02.031
we live on a tree farm,
we don't have to milk the trees.

40:02.067 --> 40:06.803
♪

40:06.838 --> 40:09.205
(PAPER RUSTLING)

40:09.241 --> 40:10.940
I've been working
on this all night

40:10.976 --> 40:13.777
and-and I like it,
I'm just, stuck.

40:14.112 --> 40:15.779
The staging area is all wrong.

40:16.081 --> 40:17.080
What do you think?

40:18.917 --> 40:21.284
But what if you made this,
the sales floor?

40:21.319 --> 40:24.053
And then you can put all the
decorations around the trees.

40:24.089 --> 40:26.289
Yes, and then that's the
first thing customers see

40:26.324 --> 40:27.590
when they arrive.

40:27.626 --> 40:33.163
♪

40:33.198 --> 40:34.164
I love it.

40:34.199 --> 40:44.274
♪

40:44.276 --> 41:13.603
♪

41:13.638 --> 41:15.138
I hear these are your specialty.

41:15.907 --> 41:16.840
Very funny.

41:16.875 --> 41:17.674
Eh?

41:17.709 --> 41:18.975
(CHUCKLES)

41:19.010 --> 41:20.477
Okay, I'll put them over here.

41:20.512 --> 41:24.581
♪

41:25.951 --> 41:32.522
♪

41:39.631 --> 41:41.397
It's so quiet here.

41:42.634 --> 41:45.635
I don't think I have ever
been anywhere this quiet.

41:47.205 --> 41:51.341
The silence is...
It's almost musical.

41:53.812 --> 41:55.278
You know, on mornings like this,

41:55.313 --> 41:58.781
when it is this quiet,
it's kinda when I hear

41:58.817 --> 42:03.052
the music the loudest, you know?

42:03.088 --> 42:06.923
Okay, I mean, it's not all
gonna be done today

42:06.958 --> 42:09.526
and it's not exactly
what I was thinking but...

42:09.561 --> 42:11.060
You're building it, step by step

42:11.096 --> 42:12.795
and you are doing it your way

42:12.831 --> 42:14.364
and that's always a good thing.

42:14.833 --> 42:16.466
<i>(HORSE NEIGHS IN DISTANCE)</i>

42:16.501 --> 42:18.101
Oh, Owen's here with the horse.

42:18.136 --> 42:19.435
(LAUGHS)

42:19.471 --> 42:24.707
♪

42:24.743 --> 42:26.743
Well they called us
down for something.

42:26.778 --> 42:27.577
<i>ADDIE: Ready?</i>

42:27.679 --> 42:28.444
I'm kinda nervous.

42:28.480 --> 42:30.113
That's a good thing,
it usually means

42:30.148 --> 42:31.681
something important
is about to happen.

42:31.783 --> 42:33.883
All right, what are
you kids up to?

42:33.919 --> 42:34.417
<i>HAILEY: Mom?</i>

42:34.452 --> 42:35.051
<i>Dad?</i>

42:35.720 --> 42:36.886
I have something to show you.

42:36.922 --> 42:38.621
Is it a large cup of coffee?

42:38.657 --> 42:40.290
Better, come on.

42:41.459 --> 42:43.760
All right, maybe it's
a pot of coffee.

42:43.795 --> 42:45.228
(LAUGHING)

42:46.665 --> 42:47.597
Hurry up.

42:51.102 --> 42:51.634
<i>Mom?</i>

42:51.670 --> 42:52.869
<i>Dad?</i>

42:52.904 --> 42:55.405
Thirty years ago, you had a
dream to start the Lapp farm and

42:55.440 --> 42:59.142
now thirty years later, I wanna
follow my dream for the farm.

42:59.177 --> 43:01.811
<i>I want to expand the business
and make the farm</i>

43:01.846 --> 43:05.515
a holiday destination spot
and it won't just be Christmas,

43:05.550 --> 43:08.651
we'll have harvest festivals
and pumpkin patches,

43:08.687 --> 43:10.653
<i>Easter egg hunts and
fourth of July barbeques.</i>

43:10.689 --> 43:13.189
Our farm will be a place that
doesn't just spread

43:13.224 --> 43:17.527
Christmas cheer,
but spreads joy all year long.

43:17.562 --> 43:19.829
And I know that we don't
have any money,

43:19.864 --> 43:22.632
but we have friends
who want to help.

43:22.667 --> 43:25.768
Addie is assisting with
the PR, Bev loaned us

43:25.804 --> 43:29.138
all of the decorations and Owen
agreed to run sleigh-rides.

43:29.174 --> 43:30.840
Owen, you're retired!

43:30.942 --> 43:32.875
There's nothing I'd
rather do with my time.

43:32.911 --> 43:35.778
Honey even with
all of this help,

43:35.814 --> 43:38.615
there's still upkeep, there's
insurance, there's marketing...

43:38.650 --> 43:40.650
We'll find a way
to make it work.

43:40.685 --> 43:42.652
<i>Every dime we have
to put into this,</i>

43:42.687 --> 43:44.887
we have to find a dime
from someplace else.

43:44.923 --> 43:46.889
I mean, it's a gamble kiddo.

43:46.925 --> 43:48.324
But it's something!

43:48.360 --> 43:49.792
We'd be doing something

43:49.828 --> 43:52.795
instead of waiting for our
home to be taken away.

43:52.831 --> 43:57.000
All I've ever wanted is this
farm and I won't give it up.

43:57.035 --> 43:59.636
Maybe this idea
could save the farm!

44:01.539 --> 44:02.905
It's ambitious.

44:02.941 --> 44:03.906
(LAUGHS)

44:03.942 --> 44:05.308
She takes after you.

44:05.410 --> 44:07.143
I remember when your mom and I

44:07.178 --> 44:09.846
first walked this piece
of property.

44:10.415 --> 44:14.651
It was a... It was
just a fallow plot,

44:14.753 --> 44:17.253
it needed a lot of work,
but your mom, she...

44:17.288 --> 44:18.855
She saw it as a home.

44:21.760 --> 44:24.861
Okay, how about we
start small and...

44:25.764 --> 44:27.530
And we'll see how it goes?

44:28.466 --> 44:30.466
(LAUGHING)

44:32.303 --> 44:33.569
<i>DALE: Get over here!</i>

44:33.605 --> 44:43.680
♪

44:43.682 --> 44:53.723
♪

44:53.758 --> 44:56.259
Hey, Hailey wanted me
to relay a message,

44:56.294 --> 44:57.860
somebody keeps calling for you?

44:57.962 --> 44:59.762
Oh, it's my manager, Russell.

44:59.798 --> 45:03.933
He wants me back on schedule,
the Palace show is in eight days

45:03.968 --> 45:06.436
and it's supposed to be
my grand unveiling

45:06.471 --> 45:09.405
where I cement my place
in country music.

45:10.108 --> 45:11.607
But, that's not what you want?

45:12.077 --> 45:13.676
Of course it is, I just...

45:13.978 --> 45:17.714
I don't know what I'm
gonna be cemented as.

45:18.450 --> 45:19.515
Hmm.

45:21.453 --> 45:23.052
I'm really proud of Hailey.

45:23.088 --> 45:25.088
Yeah, yeah me too.

45:25.190 --> 45:26.789
You know what, she's wanted this

45:26.825 --> 45:28.624
ever since she could
form a sentence.

45:29.427 --> 45:32.128
That's really hard to want
something so badly for so long

45:32.163 --> 45:34.430
and not ever know if
you're gonna get it.

45:36.301 --> 45:37.266
Yes it is.

45:38.436 --> 45:43.406
♪

45:43.441 --> 45:45.475
I'm gonna head back,
Hailey needs my help.

45:46.811 --> 45:47.810
Hey, do you...

45:48.646 --> 45:49.645
Do you wanna come?

45:50.582 --> 45:52.248
Anything to get me
away from this wreath.

45:52.283 --> 45:53.549
Is that what that is?

45:54.152 --> 45:54.784
Hey.

45:55.153 --> 46:01.491
♪

46:01.526 --> 46:03.826
So, how's the song coming?

46:03.862 --> 46:05.628
It's not really.

46:05.964 --> 46:09.565
I have a melody in
my head, it's yours.

46:09.667 --> 46:11.367
I told you, you had an earworm.

46:11.402 --> 46:13.136
You should put
some lyrics to it.

46:13.171 --> 46:14.437
No, I couldn't, it's yours.

46:14.472 --> 46:16.339
Come on, I loved
your first album.

46:16.374 --> 46:16.773
(SCOFF)

46:16.808 --> 46:18.441
My debut flop?

46:18.476 --> 46:20.443
I don't know,
maybe I'm not a writer,

46:20.478 --> 46:23.813
maybe I'm just supposed to
sing other people's music.

46:23.848 --> 46:25.815
Maybe you're just scared.

46:25.850 --> 46:26.816
What about you?

46:27.485 --> 46:28.451
What about me?

46:28.486 --> 46:29.719
You're pretty good at
that guitar of yours,

46:29.754 --> 46:33.322
why don't we flush out a song
and write something together?

46:33.358 --> 46:35.925
Motivate you,
get you out of Preston.

46:38.062 --> 46:39.962
No, I-I can't
leave now.

46:40.498 --> 46:43.666
But what if Hailey's idea
works and business picks up,

46:43.701 --> 46:45.668
you could leave then, right?

46:46.237 --> 46:47.069
I guess.

46:47.906 --> 46:51.207
It's just the music industry
is very hard.

46:51.242 --> 46:54.343
You know the difference between
a musician and a large pizza?

46:54.379 --> 46:56.512
The pizza could feed
a family of four?

46:56.548 --> 46:57.313
Yeah.

46:58.716 --> 47:00.516
Maybe I'm just
meant to stay here.

47:00.552 --> 47:01.818
Maybe you're just scared.

47:01.853 --> 47:05.888
♪

47:05.924 --> 47:07.523
(SCOFF)

47:07.625 --> 47:09.959
All right, okay, we'll try.

47:10.795 --> 47:11.427
(SCOFF)

47:11.462 --> 47:12.495
Come on.

47:14.032 --> 47:22.738
(PLAYING GUITAR)

47:23.708 --> 47:25.975
If you have the lyrics,
let's hear 'em.

47:29.614 --> 47:32.415
(PLAYING GUITAR)

47:32.450 --> 47:33.683
I can't.

47:33.718 --> 47:34.383
They're so stupid.

47:34.419 --> 47:36.052
No, you know what they say.

47:36.087 --> 47:38.754
They say, "If it's too stupid
to say, sing it."

47:40.592 --> 47:41.157
Come on.

47:42.327 --> 47:46.896
(PLAYING GUITAR)

47:46.931 --> 47:48.731
Maybe just a little faster.

47:49.167 --> 47:49.799
Faster?

47:49.834 --> 47:50.600
Yeah.

47:51.803 --> 47:54.537
<i>♪ Mmm-mmm-mm-mm ♪</i>

47:54.572 --> 47:58.107
<i>♪ Mmm-mmm-mm-mm ♪</i>

47:58.142 --> 48:01.077
<i>♪ Mmm-mmm-mm-mm ♪</i>

48:01.112 --> 48:03.880
<i>♪ Mm-mm-mm-mm-mmm ♪</i>

48:03.915 --> 48:04.780
I like it.

48:04.816 --> 48:07.750
<i>♪ It's Christmas time ♪</i>

48:07.785 --> 48:15.558
<i>♪ The snow is white, ♪
♪ a beautiful sight ♪</i>

48:15.593 --> 48:17.560
<i>♪ Let's go for a ♪
♪ sleigh-ride, baby ♪</i>

48:17.595 --> 48:19.295
And then we should go to C.

48:19.330 --> 48:22.164
<i>♪ Hearing all these ♪
♪ Christmas songs, ♪</i>

48:22.200 --> 48:25.468
<i>♪ Hearing all the ♪
♪ Christmas songs ♪</i>

48:25.503 --> 48:31.474
(HUMMING)

48:31.509 --> 48:34.110
Didn't mean to interrupt,
thought you might like to

48:34.145 --> 48:35.411
go for a
sleigh-ride.

48:38.783 --> 48:40.750
Yeah, sure, we'd love to.

48:40.785 --> 48:53.996
♪

48:54.032 --> 48:56.933
Yes, I think so, and then
there's all the extra...

48:57.835 --> 48:58.434
<i>EMMA: Who's that?</i>

48:59.203 --> 49:00.770
Are they lost, do you think?

49:01.839 --> 49:05.007
No, I think they're customers.

49:06.878 --> 49:08.277
<i>It's starting to work!</i>

49:08.913 --> 49:10.913
♪

49:12.183 --> 49:23.960
♪

49:23.995 --> 49:25.061
Wow.

49:27.131 --> 49:28.230
What's that smell?

49:29.133 --> 49:30.299
I made breakfast.

49:32.303 --> 49:33.069
What is it?

49:34.572 --> 49:35.071
No.

49:35.573 --> 49:36.806
Come on, come on.

49:36.841 --> 49:37.173
Mm-mm.

49:37.208 --> 49:38.074
What is it?

49:38.876 --> 49:41.177
It's my specialty,
something burnt.

49:42.914 --> 49:44.680
Those are not that burnt.

49:45.650 --> 49:46.315
See?

49:48.686 --> 49:50.519
(CHUCKLES)

49:51.155 --> 49:52.221
Tastes like...

49:52.256 --> 49:53.089
cement.

49:55.360 --> 49:57.860
You have some flour...

49:58.229 --> 49:59.195
right there.

50:00.431 --> 50:05.134
Should we uhh, try those again,
maybe if we do it together,

50:05.236 --> 50:06.135
it would be better.

50:07.505 --> 50:09.438
That seems to be the case.

50:10.675 --> 50:12.508
You still have...

50:12.610 --> 50:13.676
flour.

50:13.778 --> 50:17.847
♪

50:17.882 --> 50:19.515
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

50:19.550 --> 50:20.716
<i>EMMA: That's so good.</i>

50:20.752 --> 50:23.319
We just got a call for our
first sleigh ride reservation,

50:23.354 --> 50:25.321
Bev has been telling
all of her customers.

50:25.356 --> 50:26.255
What's that smell?

50:26.290 --> 50:27.390
Addie made breakfast.

50:27.425 --> 50:30.092
I was thinking about rearranging
some of the decorations,

50:30.128 --> 50:30.926
do you wanna help?

50:30.962 --> 50:32.661
Do something I'm
actually good at?

50:32.697 --> 50:34.130
I would love to.

50:38.569 --> 50:40.302
What's going on with you two?

50:40.738 --> 50:41.470
Nothing.

50:42.473 --> 50:44.206
Oh come on, I see the way
she looks at you.

50:44.242 --> 50:45.408
She doesn't look at me.

50:45.443 --> 50:48.778
I'm sorry, I know that I'm
supposed to mind my own business

50:48.813 --> 50:51.047
but you and I both know
that I can't.

50:51.082 --> 50:51.680
It's just...

50:51.716 --> 50:52.615
(SIGH)

50:53.084 --> 50:55.418
I feel like there's
something between you.

50:55.887 --> 50:57.119
Yeah, it's you.

50:57.155 --> 51:00.156
(LAUGHING)

51:00.591 --> 51:02.525
Addie's just passing through.

51:02.560 --> 51:04.160
She's gonna leave soon, so...

51:05.263 --> 51:06.095
Well.

51:07.632 --> 51:10.866
Maybe you should
think about joining her.

51:12.670 --> 51:16.038
I love having you here
at home, you know that.

51:16.074 --> 51:19.275
But I wake up every morning
and I pray that today's the day

51:19.310 --> 51:21.010
you're gonna
tell me you're going.

51:21.512 --> 51:27.049
Because this, it's all
we've ever wanted.

51:27.452 --> 51:28.451
But you...

51:29.620 --> 51:31.120
you want something else.

51:33.491 --> 51:34.390
Ma.

51:38.763 --> 51:39.862
Alright, look at this.

51:42.467 --> 51:43.232
Look at that.

51:43.267 --> 51:47.303
(TRUCK ENGINE RUMBLING)

51:47.338 --> 51:48.370
I think it's great.

51:53.211 --> 51:53.876
Hey!

51:54.812 --> 51:56.078
What's all this wood for?

51:57.348 --> 52:00.449
Well, Bev donated it all, it's
to help with the frame for this.

52:00.485 --> 52:02.184
Maybe it could be
like our emblem,

52:02.220 --> 52:04.687
the first thing that people see
when they come in.

52:04.722 --> 52:05.754
It's stunning.

52:05.790 --> 52:08.190
The two by fours are for
the frame but we still need

52:08.226 --> 52:09.959
some evergreen boughs
to weave through it.

52:09.994 --> 52:13.028
So, I was thinking that
you could collect those.

52:13.064 --> 52:14.163
Me... really?

52:14.198 --> 52:16.832
Well yeah, you know 'cause now
like I'm your new boss.

52:16.868 --> 52:17.600
Right.

52:17.635 --> 52:18.334
Yeah, of course.

52:18.369 --> 52:19.435
(LAUGHING)

52:19.470 --> 52:20.269
Hey uhh, boss?

52:21.038 --> 52:22.605
(SCOFFS)

52:24.509 --> 52:25.174
Wait.

52:26.210 --> 52:27.143
I think there's something
wrong with your arm

52:27.178 --> 52:29.845
because you used to
be able to hit me and...

52:29.881 --> 52:32.515
(LAUGHING)

52:32.550 --> 52:34.283
Good help is hard to find.

52:34.318 --> 52:36.185
(LAUGHING)

52:36.220 --> 52:38.487
Hey, Miss Addie, do you
wanna help cut down

52:38.523 --> 52:40.956
The Lapp family Christmas tree?

52:40.992 --> 52:42.091
I would love to.

52:43.394 --> 52:44.126
Come on.

52:46.731 --> 52:47.496
<i>(SIGH)</i>

52:47.532 --> 52:49.632
<i>This is something, isn't it?</i>

52:50.935 --> 52:54.637
You know, I still remember
when we first bought this land.

52:54.672 --> 52:56.805
I was a city girl, like you.

52:56.841 --> 52:59.041
I didn't know the difference
between a Christmas tree

52:59.076 --> 53:01.310
and a palm tree.

53:02.280 --> 53:07.349
My parents thought that I was
crazy and during the hard times

53:07.385 --> 53:10.886
and there's been
some hard times, I...

53:11.856 --> 53:15.224
I wonder if...
If they were right.

53:16.127 --> 53:17.860
I wonder if I made a mistake

53:17.895 --> 53:20.296
that's gonna cost
my family our home.

53:20.398 --> 53:22.164
You didn't make a mistake, Emma.

53:23.100 --> 53:25.201
You created something beautiful.

53:25.770 --> 53:28.170
This farm, your family.

53:28.206 --> 53:29.505
Yeah, that's true.

53:30.641 --> 53:35.044
My days here were, still are,
the happiest of my life.

53:36.247 --> 53:37.012
Thank you.

53:37.648 --> 53:40.282
♪

53:40.318 --> 53:44.386
Oh, yeah, that's it,
that's our Christmas tree.

53:44.422 --> 53:45.487
How do you know?

53:45.790 --> 53:49.825
The size, the shape,
the colour, the...

53:50.127 --> 53:53.696
I don't know, it's something,
it just calls to me.

53:53.965 --> 53:57.266
Uhh, this is our plan, I'm gonna
hold it steady up top here,

53:57.301 --> 54:00.903
you're gonna cut down low
and straight across.

54:01.339 --> 54:03.806
Oh, just uhh, be careful
you don't sever a limb.

54:03.841 --> 54:05.207
Mine or the tree's?

54:05.243 --> 54:05.608
(LAUGHING)

54:05.643 --> 54:06.542
Good question.

54:07.278 --> 54:09.144
There has to be an easier way

54:09.180 --> 54:12.314
to cut down a Christmas tree,
like, a chainsaw?

54:12.350 --> 54:16.885
Oh no, The Lapp Family tree
has to be cut down by hand,

54:16.921 --> 54:18.053
it's tradition.

54:19.323 --> 54:25.294
Just make slow long strokes and
you let the blade do the work.

54:25.329 --> 54:28.464
Hey, you can do this, Addie.

54:30.968 --> 54:31.867
(EXHALES)

54:33.771 --> 54:37.439
Hey, Addie just cut down
our Christmas tree.

54:37.475 --> 54:38.173
(LAUGHS)

54:38.209 --> 54:39.074
Wow!

54:39.877 --> 54:40.976
Don't you look
proud of yourself?

54:41.679 --> 54:42.411
Yup!

54:42.513 --> 54:43.779
She's a beauty, right?

54:44.448 --> 54:46.615
(LAUGHS)

54:46.651 --> 55:00.829
(GUITAR PLAYING
"THE FIRST NOËL")

55:00.865 --> 55:03.365
This was our very first ornament
when we moved here.

55:03.401 --> 55:04.366
Do you remember that?

55:04.402 --> 55:05.634
Yeah, I carved that myself.

55:05.670 --> 55:06.568
Mhm.

55:06.604 --> 55:08.370
It's always the last one
to go on the tree.

55:08.406 --> 55:09.738
Yes it is.

55:11.876 --> 55:12.941
You want me to?

55:13.177 --> 55:14.443
If you wouldn't mind.

55:14.879 --> 55:16.245
It would be an honour.

55:18.000 --> 55:24.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

55:30.394 --> 55:32.094
You cut down a good tree.

55:32.997 --> 55:35.597
Every ornament on
that tree tells a story.

55:35.700 --> 55:39.601
Our story, we have
everything we need.

55:40.671 --> 55:42.871
(SIGHS)

55:42.973 --> 55:44.139
What's the matter, sweetie?

55:45.209 --> 55:49.812
It's just, what if this is
our last Christmas here?

55:49.914 --> 55:52.147
Well then, let's make it
our best one.

55:56.187 --> 55:59.822
Uh, why don't the two of you
come help me get some cider?

55:59.924 --> 56:00.989
From the kitchen.

56:01.359 --> 56:02.191
Excuse me.

56:06.564 --> 56:09.231
Should we work on our song?

56:09.934 --> 56:10.666
Yes.

56:10.768 --> 56:11.900
(LAUGHS)

56:23.547 --> 56:24.747
You ready?

56:24.782 --> 56:25.681
Are you?

56:26.217 --> 56:27.015
We'll see.

56:27.651 --> 56:34.923
(GUITAR PLAYING)

56:34.959 --> 56:37.693
<i>♪ I'm cold, hold me, ♪</i>

56:37.728 --> 56:40.696
<i>♪ Baby, you'll see, ♪</i>

56:40.731 --> 56:46.735
<i>♪ Before every dark ♪
♪ and I'll warm you up ♪</i>

56:46.937 --> 56:52.574
(HUMMING)

56:57.815 --> 57:00.949
<i>HAILEY: I'm so sorry,
it's for you.</i>

57:05.256 --> 57:05.954
Hello?

57:11.128 --> 57:12.628
I'm not ready to go yet.

57:13.030 --> 57:13.996
Excuse me?

57:14.465 --> 57:15.697
You want to stay there?

57:15.733 --> 57:17.499
<i>But the Palace is in a week,</i>

57:17.535 --> 57:19.868
<i>we have rehearsals,
studio time, promos.</i>

57:19.904 --> 57:23.639
I know Russell,
but I'm writing a song.

57:23.674 --> 57:24.573
A good one.

57:24.608 --> 57:26.608
I thought we were
done with the writing.

57:26.644 --> 57:28.110
No, you were done.

57:28.145 --> 57:29.845
So who do you want to be?

57:29.880 --> 57:31.980
The singer who couldn't
sell an album?

57:32.016 --> 57:34.016
<i>Couldn't book a venue?</i>

57:34.051 --> 57:37.019
You're Adelaide Kay, country
super star and you have worked

57:37.054 --> 57:40.055
so hard to get here,
please don't throw it away.

57:40.090 --> 57:41.824
I'm not throwing it away.

57:41.859 --> 57:43.625
I'm just doing it my way.

57:43.661 --> 57:46.128
Adelaide, we can talk
about this when I get there.

57:46.163 --> 57:48.864
Sandra said you were on a farm,
give me the address.

57:48.899 --> 57:51.366
<i>ADELAIDE: I will call you
when I'm ready to go.</i>

57:51.402 --> 57:53.669
For now, I'm staying here.

57:53.771 --> 57:54.870
<i>RUSSELL: Adelaide,
Adelaide...</i>

57:54.905 --> 58:04.980
♪

58:04.982 --> 58:10.519
♪

58:10.554 --> 58:13.655
It's a final notice,
if we don't pay up,

58:13.691 --> 58:15.991
the bank will foreclose
January third.

58:16.026 --> 58:17.292
What are we gonna do?

58:18.295 --> 58:20.229
Well, we're not gonna cave.

58:20.331 --> 58:23.999
You had a good idea Hailey,
and it's working.

58:24.034 --> 58:26.368
Customers are coming in,
sales are up.

58:26.403 --> 58:27.202
<i>Right?</i>

58:29.740 --> 58:33.609
This is a hard time, but,
but we're going to be okay.

58:33.644 --> 58:35.711
<i>We're just going to
focus on your idea.</i>

58:35.746 --> 58:39.948
How about we, we close up
the lot in town to save money,

58:39.984 --> 58:42.384
<i>and just sell trees at the farm?</i>

58:42.653 --> 58:43.819
That's a good idea.

58:45.489 --> 58:47.456
We're not gonna
let this break us.

58:47.491 --> 58:49.791
We're not gonna let it
ruin our Christmas.

58:49.827 --> 59:02.571
♪

59:02.606 --> 59:10.078
<i>("WE WISH YOU A
MERRY CHRISTMAS" PLAYING)</i>

59:10.114 --> 59:10.946
<i>BEV: Dylan!</i>

59:11.815 --> 59:13.582
I can't believe
you're shutting down.

59:13.617 --> 59:15.951
<i>You've been here what,
nearly 20 years?</i>

59:17.288 --> 59:18.053
Yeah, well.

59:18.088 --> 59:19.288
We're just
shutting the lot down.

59:19.323 --> 59:20.822
To focus on the farm.

59:20.858 --> 59:22.424
Don't worry; We're still
going strong.

59:22.626 --> 59:25.427
Well I bought the first
Christmas tree sold here,

59:25.462 --> 59:27.930
and I want to buy
the last, so Dylan?

59:27.965 --> 59:29.731
Yes, right away.

59:31.602 --> 59:35.304
Actually, uh why don't
you help her?

59:35.339 --> 59:37.839
You want me to
sell a tree to Bev?

59:37.875 --> 59:39.007
Yeah.

59:39.043 --> 59:41.376
Why don't I just convert her
to the potted plant idea?

59:42.046 --> 59:42.945
Go.

59:43.314 --> 59:44.079
C'mon.

59:46.050 --> 59:48.617
♪

59:48.652 --> 59:50.786
Hi, I'm gonna be helping you.

59:51.722 --> 59:56.158
So this is the Spruce,
it is the most popular.

59:56.193 --> 59:58.293
It is hearty, yet elegant

59:58.329 --> 01:00:01.463
and perfect if you want to go
heavier on the decorations.

01:00:02.166 --> 01:00:05.500
Um, but, if you are
more traditional,

01:00:05.536 --> 01:00:08.470
the Douglas Fir is the go-to
with the silky needles

01:00:08.505 --> 01:00:10.772
and the iconic pine smell.

01:00:10.808 --> 01:00:13.642
Well, I am a
traditionalist, so...

01:00:14.345 --> 01:00:15.744
Oh my goodness.

01:00:18.849 --> 01:00:20.248
<i>Oh, I love this!</i>

01:00:21.251 --> 01:00:22.117
Uh, you go.

01:00:22.152 --> 01:00:23.185
I got this.

01:00:23.654 --> 01:00:24.653
I'll be right back.

01:00:24.688 --> 01:00:35.297
♪

01:00:35.332 --> 01:00:37.332
Just feeling sorry for myself.

01:00:37.368 --> 01:00:38.934
Well, don't let me ruin it.

01:00:40.104 --> 01:00:43.572
I know that I'm just supposed
to square my shoulders

01:00:43.607 --> 01:00:48.143
and soldier on but honestly,
I just want to give up.

01:00:48.245 --> 01:00:49.277
You cannot give up.

01:00:49.880 --> 01:00:50.612
Why?

01:00:51.615 --> 01:00:52.481
Because this is everything
you've always wanted,

01:00:52.516 --> 01:00:55.350
and you're so close
to seeing it through.

01:00:55.953 --> 01:00:57.486
You're inspirational.

01:00:58.122 --> 01:01:00.589
Look, five days later and you
still have me convinced

01:01:00.624 --> 01:01:02.090
that I can make a wreath.

01:01:02.126 --> 01:01:03.692
You're amazing.

01:01:04.461 --> 01:01:07.229
Well, most people like the
symbolism of a wreath

01:01:07.264 --> 01:01:08.830
more than its construction.

01:01:08.932 --> 01:01:10.532
What is the symbolism?

01:01:10.567 --> 01:01:11.233
You don't know?

01:01:11.869 --> 01:01:13.702
I didn't know what a galosh was.

01:01:14.772 --> 01:01:18.273
Well, the evergreen branches
represent strength,

01:01:18.308 --> 01:01:21.810
because they stay green even
in the harshest of winters.

01:01:22.046 --> 01:01:26.248
And the circular shape
reminds us of that every end

01:01:26.283 --> 01:01:27.683
has a new beginning.

01:01:29.887 --> 01:01:32.521
Well we have lots to do
before the tree lighting,

01:01:32.556 --> 01:01:35.390
including handing out
a whole bunch of flyers.

01:01:35.492 --> 01:01:36.258
Let's go.

01:01:38.262 --> 01:01:39.061
Thanks.

01:01:39.563 --> 01:01:40.429
There you go.

01:01:47.571 --> 01:01:48.470
Ah!

01:01:48.505 --> 01:01:50.706
I made my famous
apple pies for tonight.

01:01:50.741 --> 01:01:52.441
It smells delicious.

01:01:53.343 --> 01:01:54.743
You clean up nicely.

01:01:54.845 --> 01:01:56.344
Don't look so surprised.

01:01:58.248 --> 01:01:59.247
Addie, look!

01:02:00.217 --> 01:02:01.483
It's an early Christmas gift,
Mom made it.

01:02:01.518 --> 01:02:02.651
What do you think?

01:02:02.686 --> 01:02:03.952
It's gorgeous.

01:02:05.289 --> 01:02:06.321
For me?

01:02:06.356 --> 01:02:08.123
Mhm, and every time you wear it.

01:02:08.158 --> 01:02:10.092
I want you to think of us.

01:02:10.127 --> 01:02:11.560
I love it.

01:02:13.597 --> 01:02:14.930
What do you think?

01:02:15.966 --> 01:02:17.032
It's beautiful.

01:02:17.267 --> 01:02:29.745
♪

01:02:29.780 --> 01:02:30.779
Merry Christmas!

01:02:30.814 --> 01:02:32.047
Merry Christmas!

01:02:36.453 --> 01:02:37.185
How's it going?

01:02:37.221 --> 01:02:38.086
It's going great.

01:02:38.122 --> 01:02:39.821
Everyone's loving
the flyers for the farm.

01:02:39.857 --> 01:02:40.455
Good.

01:02:40.891 --> 01:02:47.162
♪

01:02:47.197 --> 01:02:48.430
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

01:02:48.465 --> 01:02:49.831
What did I tell you?

01:02:49.867 --> 01:02:52.134
We knew we'd find
you near the food.

01:02:52.169 --> 01:02:53.335
You know me so well.

01:02:53.370 --> 01:02:56.438
I think in times like these
you should be allowed to eat

01:02:56.473 --> 01:02:57.739
<i>all the dessert you want.</i>

01:02:57.975 --> 01:02:59.508
I still really want to help.

01:02:59.543 --> 01:03:02.010
Aw, having you here
with us has already been

01:03:02.045 --> 01:03:04.279
such a-a
wonderful gift.

01:03:04.314 --> 01:03:06.515
You're gonna come
back and visit us, right?

01:03:06.717 --> 01:03:07.949
I promise.

01:03:11.922 --> 01:03:12.988
Alright everyone!

01:03:13.023 --> 01:03:14.756
It's time for the tree lighting.

01:03:15.526 --> 01:03:17.325
<i>C'mon everyone, gather around.</i>

01:03:17.427 --> 01:03:18.326
There you are!

01:03:22.065 --> 01:03:22.864
You ready?

01:03:23.200 --> 01:03:34.543
♪

01:03:34.578 --> 01:03:36.011
<i>WOMAN: Oh, it's beautiful.</i>

01:03:36.046 --> 01:03:42.217
(APPLAUDING)

01:03:42.252 --> 01:03:43.385
It's perfect.

01:03:44.755 --> 01:03:45.520
Let's go dance.

01:03:45.556 --> 01:03:46.121
Okay.

01:03:47.457 --> 01:03:48.490
So, uh...

01:03:50.460 --> 01:03:51.860
You wanna dance?

01:03:52.296 --> 01:03:53.228
I'd love to.

01:03:57.801 --> 01:03:59.000
She's the best.

01:04:02.206 --> 01:04:04.539
Did you decide if
you're going to perform yet?

01:04:06.109 --> 01:04:09.144
Why, do you think our song
is gonna be ready in time?

01:04:09.379 --> 01:04:11.446
Not to encourage
your deflection,

01:04:11.481 --> 01:04:14.649
but I did finish
the second verse.

01:04:14.751 --> 01:04:15.517
And?

01:04:15.819 --> 01:04:16.718
It's good.

01:04:17.554 --> 01:04:18.820
Told you it would be.

01:04:20.023 --> 01:04:24.259
My whole career I had this
voice telling me to be afraid,

01:04:24.294 --> 01:04:27.195
that I'm not talented,
that I'm an imposter.

01:04:27.898 --> 01:04:32.901
And that voice is still there,
but just not listening to it.

01:04:33.637 --> 01:04:37.772
Or maybe, I just
don't believe it.

01:04:40.410 --> 01:04:42.077
(MICROPHONE FEEDBACK)

01:04:42.980 --> 01:04:44.512
Merry Christmas, Preston!

01:04:44.915 --> 01:04:46.915
<i>I know I've already
told most of you</i>

01:04:46.950 --> 01:04:48.884
<i>about the new Lapp farm.</i>

01:04:48.919 --> 01:04:53.655
So, I just wanted to say thank
you for showing me and my family

01:04:53.690 --> 01:04:55.991
so much love and support.

01:04:56.026 --> 01:05:01.963
(APPLAUDING)

01:05:01.999 --> 01:05:04.566
If I can sell a Christmas tree,
you can perform.

01:05:07.371 --> 01:05:08.970
There's a lot of people here.

01:05:09.006 --> 01:05:10.639
It's scarier to think about,

01:05:10.674 --> 01:05:12.941
it'll be easier when you
just go up there.

01:05:15.212 --> 01:05:18.480
Yeah but, what you said about
that voice inside your head

01:05:18.515 --> 01:05:19.781
saying you're not good enough,

01:05:19.816 --> 01:05:21.283
you're gonna just
mess everything up,

01:05:21.318 --> 01:05:23.585
it's screaming at me right now.

01:05:27.057 --> 01:05:27.889
I can't.

01:05:28.392 --> 01:05:35.597
♪

01:05:35.632 --> 01:05:36.298
It's okay.

01:05:38.201 --> 01:05:39.868
I'd rather dance
with you anyway.

01:05:39.903 --> 01:05:46.207
♪

01:05:46.243 --> 01:05:53.581
<i>♪ Silent night, holy night ♪</i>

01:05:56.086 --> 01:05:58.520
♪

01:05:58.555 --> 01:05:59.454
Hi, how are you?

01:05:59.489 --> 01:06:01.256
Have you seen
Adelaide Kay around town?

01:06:01.291 --> 01:06:02.390
No, no, I haven't.

01:06:02.426 --> 01:06:03.091
No, okay.

01:06:03.126 --> 01:06:04.359
Why is this so difficult?

01:06:04.394 --> 01:06:05.593
Hi there, how are you?

01:06:05.629 --> 01:06:07.362
Adelaide Kay, have you
seen her around?

01:06:07.397 --> 01:06:08.196
Oh, no, no.

01:06:08.231 --> 01:06:09.397
No, of course.

01:06:09.433 --> 01:06:11.566
Russell, Adelaide said she would
call you when she's ready.

01:06:11.601 --> 01:06:13.401
I don't have time for this.

01:06:16.073 --> 01:06:17.105
Hi, how are you?

01:06:17.975 --> 01:06:19.741
Adelaide Kay, have you seen her?

01:06:20.177 --> 01:06:21.376
Country superstar?

01:06:24.247 --> 01:06:26.314
Oh, I knew it was her.

01:06:26.350 --> 01:06:27.949
Yes, where is she?

01:06:27.985 --> 01:06:29.951
What... who are you?

01:06:29.987 --> 01:06:31.286
I'm her manager.

01:06:31.321 --> 01:06:33.088
She's at the Lapp's,
outside of town,

01:06:33.123 --> 01:06:34.389
I can give you directions.

01:06:34.424 --> 01:06:36.424
Thank you, thank you, thank you.

01:06:38.195 --> 01:06:47.802
<i>(12 DAYS OF CHRISTMAS PLAYING)</i>

01:06:47.838 --> 01:06:48.937
Hey, what's wrong?

01:06:50.140 --> 01:06:51.473
Last night, my friends said

01:06:51.508 --> 01:06:53.475
that you looked like
Adelaide Kay,

01:06:53.510 --> 01:06:58.113
so I checked online and Addie,
she really is Adelaide Kay.

01:06:58.148 --> 01:06:59.314
The singer.

01:07:01.151 --> 01:07:02.217
You already knew?

01:07:03.387 --> 01:07:04.419
Yeah.

01:07:04.788 --> 01:07:06.287
I figured it out pretty quickly.

01:07:06.323 --> 01:07:08.990
But I promised her,
I'd keep her secret.

01:07:11.128 --> 01:07:13.328
(BUS ENGINE RUMBLING)

01:07:13.363 --> 01:07:14.129
Oh no.

01:07:14.164 --> 01:07:25.507
♪

01:07:25.542 --> 01:07:26.875
What are you doing here?

01:07:26.910 --> 01:07:28.043
Adelaide, we gotta go.

01:07:28.078 --> 01:07:29.644
Palace rehearsals
start tomorrow.

01:07:29.679 --> 01:07:33.014
And I have been waiting to
tell you this in person,

01:07:33.050 --> 01:07:35.817
I got you the most coveted spot
on the nation's

01:07:35.852 --> 01:07:38.820
number one talk show,
and it is all yours.

01:07:40.057 --> 01:07:40.588
All mine?

01:07:40.624 --> 01:07:43.224
Or mine and Cole's?

01:07:43.260 --> 01:07:44.959
Ah, you and Cole this year.

01:07:44.995 --> 01:07:48.163
But you know, star crossed
lovers, holiday romance.

01:07:48.198 --> 01:07:51.299
If you stay on track, next
year this could be yours.

01:07:51.334 --> 01:07:52.200
Addie.

01:07:53.570 --> 01:07:55.870
C'mon, you don't
have to do it this way.

01:07:55.906 --> 01:07:59.874
It's the morning show, it's the
show I watched my entire life

01:07:59.910 --> 01:08:01.009
with my family.

01:08:01.044 --> 01:08:05.647
And always dreamed of
being on it and now I will be.

01:08:05.682 --> 01:08:07.549
Yeah, as
Cole Wyatt's girlfriend.

01:08:07.584 --> 01:08:10.151
This year,
but this is a huge step.

01:08:10.187 --> 01:08:10.752
Yeah, but...

01:08:10.787 --> 01:08:12.487
I have worked so hard.

01:08:12.522 --> 01:08:14.322
I have compromised so much.

01:08:14.357 --> 01:08:15.857
I cannot walk away.

01:08:19.395 --> 01:08:20.728
This is my dream.

01:08:23.265 --> 01:08:24.299
What's going on?

01:08:25.402 --> 01:08:28.670
Addie is really Adelaide Kay,
some famous singer.

01:08:28.705 --> 01:08:30.138
I'm not famous.

01:08:30.407 --> 01:08:33.408
<i>I'm sorry I didn't
tell you who I was.</i>

01:08:33.910 --> 01:08:36.144
I liked being just Addie.

01:08:40.951 --> 01:08:41.749
Okay, c'mon.

01:08:41.785 --> 01:08:42.850
Let's go.

01:08:42.886 --> 01:08:52.926
♪

01:08:52.929 --> 01:08:59.767
♪

01:08:59.803 --> 01:09:00.702
(DOOR CLOSING)

01:09:03.305 --> 01:09:04.339
<i>(HONKING)</i>

01:09:07.810 --> 01:09:09.777
After this, we have
rehearsal for the Palace,

01:09:09.813 --> 01:09:11.645
tomorrow the Morning Show.

01:09:11.680 --> 01:09:13.314
Adelaide you're
going to be amazing.

01:09:13.350 --> 01:09:16.084
I still have those Christmas
jokes if you want them.

01:09:19.356 --> 01:09:23.992
Adelaide, I know you're upset,
but you made your own decision.

01:09:24.027 --> 01:09:24.893
Alright?

01:09:24.928 --> 01:09:27.595
You need to focus
on what's positive.

01:09:27.631 --> 01:09:28.395
You're a star.

01:09:29.332 --> 01:09:31.566
And we make
sacrifices for stardom.

01:09:32.935 --> 01:09:34.269
Sacrifices?

01:09:34.371 --> 01:09:35.970
What sacrifices
have you made, Russell?

01:09:36.006 --> 01:09:40.140
Because I've sacrificed my name,
my family, my integrity.

01:09:40.176 --> 01:09:42.343
Do I really have
to sacrifice my heart?

01:09:42.379 --> 01:09:43.978
When is this enough?!

01:09:47.216 --> 01:09:48.850
Let's give her a minute.

01:09:48.885 --> 01:09:58.960
♪

01:09:58.962 --> 01:10:14.776
♪

01:10:14.811 --> 01:10:15.910
How are you doing?

01:10:22.018 --> 01:10:23.318
What's wrong?

01:10:24.554 --> 01:10:30.024
Uhm, Mom just did the books
and she says that sales are up.

01:10:30.060 --> 01:10:33.494
Way up actually, but uhm,

01:10:33.997 --> 01:10:36.297
we're still not gonna have
the money in time.

01:10:37.100 --> 01:10:38.433
We're gonna lose the farm.

01:10:40.403 --> 01:10:41.836
But I'm not giving up.

01:10:41.871 --> 01:10:44.005
Because I still somehow think

01:10:44.040 --> 01:10:46.107
everything is going to be okay.

01:10:46.376 --> 01:10:52.614
And if it's not okay then,
at least I can say that I tried.

01:10:57.921 --> 01:11:00.321
And it's about time
that you tried too, Dylan.

01:11:00.724 --> 01:11:03.491
I know that you're worried
about leaving us,

01:11:03.526 --> 01:11:05.827
but we're gonna be fine.

01:11:06.396 --> 01:11:07.629
I promise.

01:11:09.032 --> 01:11:10.031
I worry about you guys.

01:11:12.469 --> 01:11:15.403
What if I do this thing
that I've wanted forever,

01:11:16.706 --> 01:11:20.708
and I find out that
I'm just not good enough?

01:11:21.044 --> 01:11:24.178
You are good enough,
you're great.

01:11:26.483 --> 01:11:31.085
As is this hot chocolate,
and I just made a fresh batch.

01:11:31.121 --> 01:11:32.220
Do you want some?

01:11:33.123 --> 01:11:35.189
Wow, way to bury the lead.

01:11:35.225 --> 01:11:36.257
(LAUGHS)

01:11:38.762 --> 01:11:48.836
♪

01:11:48.838 --> 01:12:18.933
♪

01:12:18.968 --> 01:12:19.734
Hey.

01:12:22.939 --> 01:12:24.939
I haven't seen you
this sad since...

01:12:24.974 --> 01:12:26.507
My first album flopped?

01:12:26.543 --> 01:12:29.310
I didn't know how to make
you feel better then either.

01:12:32.115 --> 01:12:33.681
Russell says this is my chance

01:12:33.717 --> 01:12:36.951
to cement myself in
country music but,

01:12:36.986 --> 01:12:39.253
what if this isn't what
I want to cement?

01:12:39.556 --> 01:12:43.558
Dylan made me think about
that, about who I really am.

01:12:43.660 --> 01:12:44.726
Adelaide...

01:12:45.061 --> 01:12:46.928
you know who you are.

01:12:47.030 --> 01:12:48.863
You always have deep down,

01:12:48.898 --> 01:12:51.432
but you just need to believe
that it's good enough.

01:12:51.468 --> 01:12:54.435
I wish that you could see
yourself the way that I do.

01:12:54.471 --> 01:12:56.237
Or the way that Dylan does.

01:12:58.541 --> 01:13:00.875
And that album was good.

01:13:00.910 --> 01:13:02.477
It really was.

01:13:02.579 --> 01:13:04.545
Let the world see that Adelaide.

01:13:04.581 --> 01:13:05.413
(KNOCKING)

01:13:05.448 --> 01:13:06.547
Ready for the
Morning Show tomorrow?

01:13:06.583 --> 01:13:09.650
<i>You read the script the
PR team sent over, right?</i>

01:13:09.686 --> 01:13:11.686
It doesn't have to
be word for word,

01:13:11.721 --> 01:13:13.287
just focus on you and Cole.

01:13:13.323 --> 01:13:15.957
Country Christmas,
how happy you two are.

01:13:15.992 --> 01:13:16.824
<i>Et cetera.</i>

01:13:17.260 --> 01:13:17.992
Got it.

01:13:19.329 --> 01:13:20.094
Great.

01:13:23.333 --> 01:13:24.499
What's that look?

01:13:25.168 --> 01:13:26.667
What are you gonna do?

01:13:26.703 --> 01:13:30.505
♪

01:13:31.775 --> 01:13:33.441
♪

01:13:33.476 --> 01:13:35.943
It seems our viewers can't
get enough of the Prince

01:13:35.979 --> 01:13:38.379
and Princess of country pop.

01:13:38.815 --> 01:13:41.916
So Adelaide,
you have a hit song.

01:13:42.018 --> 01:13:44.185
Does this all seem
like a fairy tale?

01:13:44.587 --> 01:13:47.422
Yeah, it does seem
like a fairy tale.

01:13:48.458 --> 01:13:52.493
But honestly it feels
more like a fantasy

01:13:53.329 --> 01:13:57.098
because I'm not
actually dating Cole.

01:13:57.200 --> 01:14:00.435
<i>It was a rumour someone
started, PR stunt.</i>

01:14:00.470 --> 01:14:02.036
And I know what you're thinking,

01:14:02.071 --> 01:14:05.773
"How could
anyone do that?"

01:14:06.309 --> 01:14:09.777
So I want to
apologize to my fans

01:14:09.813 --> 01:14:12.447
from the bottom of my heart.

01:14:12.816 --> 01:14:13.381
What...

01:14:14.384 --> 01:14:16.451
And the truth is I did
have a special someone,

01:14:16.786 --> 01:14:21.122
he's a man who believed
in my music and in me.

01:14:22.091 --> 01:14:25.793
So, Dylan, if you're
watching this,

01:14:25.829 --> 01:14:30.064
and to Hailey, Emma, and Dale,
thank you so much

01:14:30.099 --> 01:14:31.966
for everything you've given me.

01:14:33.937 --> 01:14:38.272
Wow, uhm, this is quite the
interesting turn of events here.

01:14:38.308 --> 01:14:39.774
<i>Let's go to commercial break.</i>

01:14:42.679 --> 01:14:44.612
Adelaide, that was a disaster.

01:14:46.316 --> 01:14:47.815
Also known as the truth.

01:14:48.852 --> 01:14:51.752
Russell, I love music.

01:14:51.855 --> 01:14:54.188
I live for it,
and you know what?

01:14:54.224 --> 01:14:55.022
I'm good at it.

01:14:56.359 --> 01:14:59.827
And I've worked
a lifetime to get here

01:14:59.863 --> 01:15:02.396
and I'm ready to do it my way.

01:15:02.665 --> 01:15:04.465
Adelaide,
you gotta believe in me.

01:15:04.501 --> 01:15:06.968
What about believing in me?

01:15:07.470 --> 01:15:08.769
You know what, nevermind.

01:15:08.872 --> 01:15:11.839
Because now,
I believe in myself.

01:15:12.509 --> 01:15:16.143
I'm so grateful for everything
that you've done for me Russell.

01:15:16.179 --> 01:15:19.547
And if we can do
things a different way,

01:15:19.582 --> 01:15:22.717
my way, then I would
love to do it together.

01:15:22.752 --> 01:15:32.827
♪

01:15:32.829 --> 01:15:40.568
♪

01:15:40.603 --> 01:15:52.046
(CHEERING)

01:15:52.081 --> 01:15:54.815
Adelaide, I want to
be just like you.

01:15:55.051 --> 01:15:57.752
Just be yourself,
'cause that's even better.

01:15:57.787 --> 01:15:58.619
Thank you!

01:16:02.959 --> 01:16:04.492
I thought you weren't a fan.

01:16:05.762 --> 01:16:07.728
Well, what can I say?

01:16:07.764 --> 01:16:09.063
I like your new stuff.

01:16:09.799 --> 01:16:10.631
I'm sorry.

01:16:12.402 --> 01:16:13.467
I was scared.

01:16:14.237 --> 01:16:15.703
I thought I was walking away

01:16:15.738 --> 01:16:17.572
from everything
I've ever wanted.

01:16:17.607 --> 01:16:21.475
But, it's actually
not what I want at all.

01:16:22.545 --> 01:16:23.544
Yeah, I get it.

01:16:25.448 --> 01:16:26.581
And you were right.

01:16:27.817 --> 01:16:31.018
I've been so afraid of failing,
that's why I haven't tried.

01:16:32.822 --> 01:16:33.654
How's the farm?

01:16:35.725 --> 01:16:40.361
Sales are up, but we're not
going to make it in time.

01:16:40.597 --> 01:16:42.163
Let me help, please.

01:16:43.600 --> 01:16:45.566
I could do a Christmas concert,

01:16:45.602 --> 01:16:48.569
and all the money could
go to save the farm.

01:16:49.105 --> 01:16:50.504
But when, on Christmas Eve?

01:16:50.607 --> 01:16:52.373
That's the night of
your Palace show.

01:16:52.609 --> 01:16:55.710
I'd rather do this because that
Palace gig was supposed to be

01:16:55.745 --> 01:17:00.881
what showed the world
who I was, but this,

01:17:00.917 --> 01:17:02.950
this is who I really am.

01:17:03.920 --> 01:17:05.086
That's really generous.

01:17:05.955 --> 01:17:09.090
And it would be a
miracle if it worked.

